\id ACT Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h Acts
\mt1 The Acts of the Apostles.
\c 1
\p
\v 1 \sc The\sc* first treatise I made of all things, O Theophilus, which \sc Jesus\sc* began to do and to teach, \f + \fr 1:1 \ft The Epistle at Mass upon Ascension day.\f* \f + \fr 1:1 \ft Not all particularly, (for the other Evangelists write diverse things not touched by him) but all the principal and most necessary things.\f* \x + \xo 1:1 \xt Lu. 1, 3.\x*
\v 2 until the day wherein giving commandment by the Holy Ghost to the Apostles whom he chose, he was assumpted.
\v 3 to whom he shewed also himself alive after his passion in many arguments, for forty days appearing to them, and speaking of the Kingdom of God.
\v 4 And eating with them, he commanded them, that they should not depart from Jerusalem, but should expect the promise of the Father, which you have heard (saith he) by my mouth: \x + \xo 1:4 \xt Lu. 24, 49.\x* \x + \xo 1:4 \xt Io. 14, 26.\x*
\v 5 for John indeed baptized with water, but you shall be baptized with the Holy Ghost after these few days. \f + \fr 1:5 \ft John's Baptism gave not the Holy Ghost.\f* \f + \fr 1:5 \ft The aboundant pouring of the Holy Ghost upon them on Whitsunday, he calleth Baptism.\f* \x + \xo 1:5 \xt Lu. 3, 16.\x*
\v 6 They therefore that were assembled, asked him, saying: Lord, whether at this time wilt thou restore the Kingdom to Israel?
\v 7 but he said to them: It is not for you to know times or moments, which the Father hath put in his own power:
\v 8 but you shall receive the virtue of the Holy Ghost coming upon you, and you shall be witnesses unto me in Jerusalem, and in all Jewry, and Samaria, and even to the utmost of the earth. \x + \xo 1:8 \xt Lu. 24, 49. Act. 2, 1.\x*
\v 9 And when he had said these things, in their sight he was elevated: & a cloud received him out of their sight. \x + \xo 1:9 \xt Mar. 16, 19. Lu. 24, 51.\x*
\v 10 And when they beheld him going into Heaven, behold two men stood beside them in white garments,
\v 11 who also said: Ye men of Galilee, why stand you looking into Heaven? This \sc Jesus\sc* which is assumpted from you into Heaven, shall so come as you have seen him going into Heaven.
\v 12 Then they returned to Jerusalem from the mount that is called Olivet, which is by Jerusalem, distant a Sabboth's journey.
\v 13 And when they were entered in, they went up into an upper chamber, where abode Peter & John, James and Andrew, Philippe and Thomas, Bartholomew and Matthew, James of Alphæus and Simon Zelotes, and Jude of James. \f + \fr 1:13 \ft This visible company was the true Church of Christ, which he left, & commanded to keep together till the coming of the Holy Ghost, by Him to be further informed & furnished to gain all nations to the same Society.\f*
\v 14 All these were persevering with one mind in prayer with the women and \sc Mary\sc* the mother of \sc Jesus\sc*, and his brethren. \f + \fr 1:14 \ft The Heretics, some in the text, other in the margent, translate, wives, to wit, of the Apostles, most impudently, knowing in their consciences that he meaneth the Marys & other holy women that followed Christ as Lu. 8, 2. 24, 10. See Beza & the Engl. Bible 1579.\f*
\v 15 In those days Peter rising up in the midst of the Brethren, said: (and the multitude of persons together, was almost an hundred and twenty.) \f + \fr 1:15 \ft a The Epistle upon S. Matthias day Febr. 24.\f*
\v 16 You men, brethren, the scripture must be fulfilled which the Holy Ghost spake before by the mouth of David concerning Judas, who was the captain of them that apprehended \sc Jesus\sc*: \x + \xo 1:16 \xt Ps. 40, 9. Io. 13, 18.\x* \x + \xo 1:16 \xt Luc. 22, 47. Io. 18, 3.\x*
\v 17 who was numbered among us and obtained the lot of this ministry.
\v 18 And he indeed hath possessed a field of the reward of iniquity, and being hanged he burst in the midst, and all his bowels gushed out. \x + \xo 1:18 \xt Mt. 27, 5. 7.\x*
\v 19 And it was made notorious to all the inhabitants of Jerusalem: so that the same field was called in their tongue, \add Hacel-dema,\add* that is to say, the field of blood.
\v 20 For it is written in the book of Psalms: \add Be their habitation made desert, & be there none to dwell in it. \add* \add And his Bishopric let another take.\add* \x + \xo 1:20 \xt Psa. 68, 26.\x* \x + \xo 1:20 \xt Ps. 108, 8.\x*
\v 21 Therefore, of these men that have assembled with us, all the time that our Lord \sc Jesus\sc* went in and went out among us,
\v 22 beginning from the Baptism of John until the day wherein he was assumpted from us, there must one of these be made a witness with us of his resurrection. \f + \fr 1:22 \ft No small mystery, that the number of the twelve Apostles must needs be made up again.\f*
\v 23 And they appointed two, Joseph, who was called Barsabas, who was surnamed Justus: and Matthias.
\v 24 And praying they said: Thou Lord that knowest the hearts of all men, shew of these two, one, whom thou hast chosen,
\v 25 to take the place of this ministry & Apostleship, from the which Judas hath prevaricated that he might go to his own place.
\v 26 And they gave them lots, and the lot fell upon Matthias, and he was numbered with the eleven Apostles.
\c 2
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* when the days of Pentecost were accomplished, they were all together in one place: \f + \fr 2:1 \ft The Epistle upon Whitsunday.\f* \x + \xo 2:1 \xt Act. 1, 4.\x*
\v 2 and suddenly there was made a sound from Heaven, as of a vehement wind coming, & it filled the whole house where they were sitting.
\v 3 And there appeared to them parted tongues as it were of fire, and it sat upon every one of them: \x + \xo 2:3 \xt Mt. 3, 11.\x*
\v 4 and they were all replenished with the \sc Holy Ghost\sc*, and they began to speak with diverse tongues, according as the \sc Holy Ghost\sc* gave them to speak. \x + \xo 2:4 \xt Io. 7, 39.\x*
\v 5 And there were dwelling at Jerusalem Jews, devout men of every nation that is under Heaven.
\v 6 And when this voice was made, the multitude came together, and was astonished in mind, because every man heard them speak in his own tongue.
\v 7 And they were all amazed, and marveled saying: Are not, lo, all these that speak, Galilæans,
\v 8 and how <alt>have we heard</alt>, each man our own tongue wherein we were born? \f + \fr 2:8 \ft do we hear.\f*
\v 9 Parthians, & Medians, & Elamites, & that inhabit Mesopotamia, Jewry, & Cappadocia, Pontus, and Asia,
\v 10 Phrygia, and Pamphilia, Ægypt & the parts of Libya that is about Cyrenee, & strangers of Rome,
\v 11 Jews also, and Proselytes, Cretensians, and Arabians: we <alt>have heard</alt> them speak in our own tongues the great works of God. \f + \fr 2:11 \ft do hear\f*
\v 12 And they were all astonished, and marveled, saying one to another: What meaneth this?
\v 13 But others deriding said: That these are full of new wine.
\v 14 But Peter standing with the Eleven, lifted up his voice; and spake to them: Ye men, Jews, and all you that dwell in Jerusalem, be this known to you, and with your ears receive my words. \f + \fr 2:14 \ft a The lesson before the Epistle on Imber Wednesday in Whitsunweek.\f* \f + \fr 2:14 \ft Peter the head of the rest and now newly replenished with all knowledge and fortitude, maketh the first Sermon.\f*
\v 15 For these are not drunk, as you suppose, whereas it is the third hour of the day:
\v 16 But this is it that was said by the Prophet Joel:
\v 17 \add And it shall be, in the last days (saith our Lord) of my Spirit I will pour out upon all flesh: and your sons and your daughters shall prophesy, and your young men shall see visions, and your Ancients shall dream dreams.\add* \x + \xo 2:17 \xt Ioel. 2, 28.\x*
\v 18 \add and upon my servants truly, and upon my handmaids will I pour out in those days, of my Spirit, and they shall prophesy:\add*
\v 19 \add and I will give wonders in the Heaven above, and signs in the earth beneath, blood and fire, and vapour of smoke.\add*
\v 20 \add The sun shall be turned into darkness, and the moon into blood, before the great and manifest day of our Lord doth come.\add*
\v 21 \add And it shall be, every one whosoever calleth upon the name of our Lord, shall be saved.\add*
\v 22 Ye men of Israel hear these words: \sc Jesus\sc* of Nazareth a man approved of God among you, by miracles & wonders and signs which God did by him in the midst of you, as you also know;
\v 23 this same, by the determinate counsel & prescience of God being delivered, you by the hands of wicked men have crucified and slain.
\v 24 Whom God hath raised up loosing the sorrows of hell, according as it was impossible that he should be holden of it.
\v 25 For David saith concerning him: \add I foresaw the Lord in my sight always: because he is at my right hand that I be not moved.\add* \x + \xo 2:25 \xt Ps. 15, 8.\x*
\v 26 \add For this, my heart hath been glad and my tongue hath rejoiced: moreover my flesh also shall rest in hope.\add*
\v 27 \add Because thou wilt not leave my soul \add* \add in hell, nor give thy Holy one to see \add* \add corruption.\add* \f + \fr 2:27 \ft Who but an infidel (saith S. Augustine) will deny Christ to have descended to Hell? ep. 99.\f* \f + \fr 2:27 \ft As his soul suffered no pains in Hell, so neither did his body take any corruption in the grave.\f*
\v 28 \add Thou hast made known to me the ways of life: thou shalt make me full of joyfulness with thy face.\add*
\v 29 Ye men, Brethren, let me boldly speak to you of the Patriarch David: that he died, and was buried; and his sepulchre is with us until this present day. \x + \xo 2:29 \xt 3. Reg. 2, 10.\x*
\v 30 Whereas therefore he was a Prophet, and knew that by an oath \add God hath sworn to him, that of the fruit of his loins there should sit upon his seat;\add* \x + \xo 2:30 \xt Ps. 131, 11.\x*
\v 31 foreseeing, he spake of the resurrection of Christ, for neither was he left in hell, neither did his flesh see corruption.
\v 32 This \sc Jesus\sc* hath God raised again, whereof all we are witnesses.
\v 33 Being exalted therefore by the right hand of God, and having received of his Father the promise of the Holy Ghost, he hath poured out <alt>this whom</alt> you see and hear. \f + \fr 2:33 \ft this gift which\f*
\v 34 For David ascended not into Heaven; but he saith: \add Our Lord hath said to my Lord, sit on my right hand.\add* \x + \xo 2:34 \xt Ps. 109, 1.\x*
\v 35 \add until I make thine enemies the foot-stool of thy feet.\add*
\v 36 Therefore let all the house of Israel know most certainly that God hath made him both Lord, & \sc Christ\sc*, this \sc Jesus\sc*, whom you have crucified.
\v 37 And hearing these things, they were compunct in heart, and said to Peter and to the rest of the Apostles: What shall we do men, brethren. \f + \fr 2:37 \ft Contrition.\f*
\v 38 But Peter said to them, do penance, & be every one of you baptized in the name of \sc Jesus Christ\sc* for remission of your sins; and you shall receive the gift of the Holy Ghost. \f + \fr 2:38 \ft Not only amendment of life, but penance also required before Baptism, in such as be of age, though not in that sort as afterward in the Sacrament of penance. Aug. de fid. et oper. c. 11. et ep. 108.\f*
\v 39 For to you is the promise, and to your children, and to all that are far off, whomsoever the Lord our God shall call.
\v 40 With very many other words also did he testify and exhorted them, saying: Save yourselves from this perverse Generation.
\v 41 They therefore that received his word, were baptized: & there were added in that day about three thousand souls. \f + \fr 2:41 \ft Three thousand were converted at this first sermon, & they were put to the other visible company and Church.\f*
\v 42 And they were persevering in the doctrine of the Apostles, and in the communication of the breaking of bread, and prayers. \f + \fr 2:42 \ft c This was the B. Sacrament, which the Apostles daily ministered to the Christians at least in one kind. See chap. 20, 7.\f*
\v 43 And fear came upon every soul; many wonders also and signs were done by the Apostles in Jerusalem, and there was great fear in all.
\v 44 All they also that believed, were together, & had all things common. \x + \xo 2:44 \xt Act. 4, 32.\x*
\v 45 Their possessions and substance they sold, and divided them to all, according as every one had need.
\v 46 Daily also continuing with one accord in the temple, and breaking bread from house to house, they took their meat with joy and simplicity of heart:
\v 47 praising God, and having grace with all the people. And our Lord increased them that should be saved, daily together.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* Peter and John went up into the temple, at the ninth hour of prayer. \f + \fr 3:1 \ft The Epistle upon SS. Peter and Paul's eve. Iun. 28.\f* \f + \fr 3:1 \ft This maketh for distinction of Canonical hours and diversity of appointed times to pray in. See Annot. c. 10, 9.\f*
\v 2 And a certain man that was lame from his mother's womb, was carried; whom they laid every day at the gate of the temple, that is called Specious, that he might ask alms of them that went into the temple.
\v 3 He, when he had seen Peter and John about to enter into the temple, asked to receive an alms.
\v 4 But Peter with John looking upon him, said: Look upon us.
\v 5 But he looked earnestly upon them, hoping that he should receive something of them.
\v 6 But Peter said: Silver and gold I have not, but that which I have, the same I give to thee: In the name of \sc Jesus Christ\sc* of Nazareth arise, and walk.
\v 7 And taking his right hand, he lifted him up, and forthwith his feet & soles were made strong.
\v 8 And springing he stood, & walked; & went in with them into the temple walking, and leaping, and praising God.
\v 9 And all the people saw him walking and praising God.
\v 10 And they knew him, that it was he which sat for alms at the Specious gate of the temple: and they were exceedingly astonished and aghast at that that had chanced to him.
\v 11 And as he held Peter and John, all the people ran to them unto the porch which is called Salomon's, wondering.
\v 12 But Peter seeing them, made answer to the people: Ye men of Israel, why marvel you at this, or why look you upon us, as though by our power or holiness we have made this man to walk? \f + \fr 3:12 \ft The Epistle upon Wednesday in Easter week.\f*
\v 13 The God of Abraham, and the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob, the God of our fathers hath glorified his Son \sc Jesus\sc*, whom you indeed delivered & denied before the face of Pilate, he judging him to be released.
\v 14 But you denied the Holy and the Just One, and asked a man-killer to be given unto you. \x + \xo 3:14 \xt Luc. 23, 18.\x*
\v 15 But the Author of life you killed, whom God hath raised from the dead, of which we are witnesses.
\v 16 And in the faith of his name, this man whom you see and know, his name hath strengthened; & the faith which is by him, hath given this perfect health in the sight of all you. \f + \fr 3:16 \ft This faith was not the faith of the lame man (for he looked only for alms) nor a special faith of the Apostle's own salvation: but the whole belief of Christian Religion.\f*
\v 17 And now (brethren) I know that you did it through ignorance, as also your princes.
\v 18 But God who foreshewed by the mouth of all the Prophets that his \sc Christ\sc* should suffer, hath so fulfilled it.
\v 19 Be Penitent therefore & convert, that your sins may be put out.
\v 20 That, when the times shall come of refreshing by the sight of our Lord, and he shall send him that hath been preached unto you \sc Jesus Christ\sc*.
\v 21 Whom Heaven truly must receive until the times of the restitution of all things, which God spake by the mouth of his holy Prophets from the beginning of the world. \f + \fr 3:21 \ft c ὃν δεῖ οὐρανὸν μὲν δέξασθαι\f* \f + \fr 3:21 \ft Some Heretics foully corrupt this place, thus: Who must be contained in heaven, of purpose (as they protest) to hold Christ in heaven, from the B. Sacrament. Beza. As though his presence there, drew him out of heaven. Neither can they pretend the Greek, which is word for word as in the vulgar Latin, and as we translate.\f*
\v 22 Moyses indeed said: \add That a prophet shall the\add* Lord your God raise up to you of your brethren, as \add myself: him you shall hear according to all things whatsoever he shall speak to you.\add* \x + \xo 3:22 \xt Deu. 18, 15.\x*
\v 23 \add And it shall be, every soul that shall not hear that Prophet, shall be destroyed out of the people.\add*
\v 24 And all the Prophets from Samuel and afterward that have spoken, told of these days.
\v 25 You are the children of the Prophets and of the Testament which God made to our fathers, saying to Abraham: \add And in thy seed shall all the families of the earth be blessed.\add* \x + \xo 3:25 \xt Gen. 22, 18. 26, 4.\x*
\v 26 To you first God raising up his Son, hath sent him blessing you: that every one should convert himself from his naughtiness.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* when they were speaking to the people, the Priests and Magistrates of the temple & the Sadducees came upon them,
\v 2 being grieved that they taught the people, and shewed in \sc Jesus\sc* the resurrection from the dead:
\v 3 and they laid hands upon them, and put them into ward, until the morrow, for it was now evening.
\v 4 And many of them that had heard the word, believed: and the number of the men was made five thousand. \f + \fr 4:4 \ft Here again we see the proceeding and increase of the Church visibly.\f*
\v 5 And it came to pass on the morrow, that their princes, and Ancients, and Scribes were gathered into Jerusalem.
\v 6 And Annas the high Priest, and Caiphas and John, and Alexander, and as many as were of the priest's stock.
\v 7 And setting them in the midst, they asked: In what power or in what name have you done this?
\v 8 Then Peter replenished with the Holy Ghost, said to them: Ye princes of the people and Ancients:
\v 9 If we this day be examined for a good deed upon an impotent man, in what he hath been made whole,
\v 10 be it known to all you and to all the people of Israel, that in the name of \sc Jesus Christ\sc* of Nazareth, whom you did crucify, whom God hath raised from the dead, in this same this man standeth before you whole. \f + \fr 4:10 \ft The name of JESUS. See Annot. Philip. 2, 10.\f*
\v 11 This is \add the stone that was rejected of you the builders: which is made into the head of the corner:\add* \x + \xo 4:11 \xt Psa. 117, 22.\x*
\v 12 and there is not salvation in any other. For neither is there any other name under Heaven given to men, wherein we must be saved.
\v 13 And seeing Peter's constancy and John's, understanding that they were men unlettered, and of the vulgar sort, they marveled; and they knew them that they had been with \sc Jesus\sc*: \f + \fr 4:13 \ft The Apostles' constancy, learning and wisdom after the coming of the Holy Ghost, being but idiots, that is, simple unlettered men and timorous before.\f*
\v 14 seeing the man also that had been cured, standing with them, they could say nothing to the contrary,
\v 15 But they commanded them to go aside forth out of the council: and they conferred together,
\v 16 saying: What shall we do to these men? for a notorious sign indeed hath been done by them, to all the inhabitants of Jerusalem: it is manifest, and we cannot deny it.
\v 17 But that it be no further spread abroad among the people, let us threaten them, that they speak no more in this name to any man.
\v 18 And calling them, they charged them that they should not speak at all, nor teach in the name of \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 19 But Peter and John answering, said to them: If it be just in the sight of God, to hear you rather than God, judge ye. \f + \fr 4:19 \ft Their constancy and courage after their confirmation, being so weak before. And if any Magistrate command against God, that is to say, forbid Catholic Christian men to preach or serve God, this same must be their answer, though they be whipped and killed for their labour. See c. 5. v. 29.\f*
\v 20 For we cannot but speak the things which we have seen and heard.
\v 21 But they threatening, dismissed them: not finding how they might punish them, for the people, because all glorified that which had been done, in that which was chanced.
\v 22 For the man was more than forty years old in whom that sign of health had been wrought.
\v 23 And being dismissed they came to theirs, and shewed all that the chief priests and Ancients had said to them.
\v 24 Who having heard it, with one accord lifted up their voice to God, and said: Lord, thou that didst make Heaven & earth, the sea, and all things that are in them,
\v 25 who in the Holy Ghost by the mouth of our Father David thy servant hast said: \add Why did the Gentiles rage, and the people meditate vain things:\add* \x + \xo 4:25 \xt Ps. 2, 1.\x*
\v 26 \add the kings of the earth stand up, and the Princes assemble together against our Lord, and against his \sc Christ\sc*?\add*
\v 27 For there assembled indeed in this city against the holy child \sc Jesus\sc* whom thou hast anointed, Herod, and Pontius Pilate, with the Gentiles and the people of Israel;
\v 28 to do what thy hand and thy counsel decreed to be done. \f + \fr 4:28 \ft Christ's death, as needful for man's redemption, was of God's determination: but as of the malice of the Jews, it was not his act otherwise than by permission.\f*
\v 29 And now Lord look upon their threatenings, and give unto thy servants with all confidence to speak thy word,
\v 30 in that, that thou extend thy hand to cures & signs and wonders to be done by the name of thy holy son \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 31 And when they had prayed, the place was moved wherein they were gathered: and they were all replenished with the Holy Ghost, and they spake the word of God with confidence.
\v 32 And the multitude of believers had one heart and one soul: neither did any one say that ought was his own of those things which he possessed, but all things were common unto them. \x + \xo 4:32 \xt Act. 2, 44.\x*
\v 33 And with great power did the Apostles give testimony of the resurrection of \sc Jesus Christ\sc* our Lord: and great grace was in all them.
\v 34 For neither was there any one needy among them. For as many as were owners of lands or houses, sold and brought the prices of those things which they sold, \f + \fr 4:34 \ft Note the ardent charity and contempt of worldly things in the first Christians: who did not only give great alms, but\f*
\v 35 and laid it before the feet of the Apostles. And to every one was divided according as every one had need.
\v 36 And Joseph who was surnamed of the Apostles Barnabas (which is by interpretation, the son of consolation) a Levite, a Cyprian born,
\v 37 whereas he had a piece of land, sold it, and brought the price, and laid it before the feet of the Apostles.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 \sc But\sc* a certain man named Ananias, with Saphira his wife sold a piece of land,
\v 2 and defrauded of the price of the land, his wife being privy thereto: and bringing a certain portion, laid it at the feet of the Apostles.
\v 3 And Peter said: Ananias, why hath Satan tempted thy heart, that thou shouldest lie to the Holy Ghost, and defraud of the price of the land?
\v 4 Remaining, did it not remain to thee: and being sold, was it not in thy power? Why hast thou put this thing in thy heart? Thou hast not lied to men, but to God.
\v 5 And Ananias hearing these words, fell down, and gave up the ghost. And there came great fear upon all that heard it.
\v 6 And young men rising up, removed him, & bearing him forth buried him.
\v 7 And it was the space as it were of three hours, and his wife, not knowing what was chanced, came in.
\v 8 And Peter answered her: Tell me woman, whether did you sell the land for so much? But she said: Yea, for so much.
\v 9 And Peter unto her: Why have you agreed together to tempt the Spirit of our Lord? Behold, their feet that have buried thy husband, at the door, and they shall bear thee forth.
\v 10 Forthwith she fell before his feet, and gave up the ghost. And the young men going in, found her dead: and carried her forth, & buried her by her husband.
\v 11 And there fell great fear in the whole Church, and upon all that heard these things. \f + \fr 5:11 \ft Hereupon rose great reverence, awe, and fear of the vulgar Christians toward the holy Apostles; for an example to all Christian people how to behave themselves toward their Bishops and Priests.\f*
\v 12 And by the hands of the Apostles were many signs and wonders done among the people. And they were all with one accord in Salomon's porch. \f + \fr 5:12 \ft The Epistle upon Imber Wednesday in Whitsunweek. And within the octave, & in a votive of SS. Peter and Paul.\f*
\v 13 But of the rest none durst join themselves unto them: but the people magnified them.
\v 14 And the multitude of men and women that believed in our Lord, was more increased:
\v 15 so that they did bring forth the sick into the streets, & laid them in beds and couches, that when Peter came, his shadow at the least might overshadow any of them, and they all might be delivered from their infirmities. \f + \fr 5:15 \ft Peter's shadow.\f*
\v 16 And there ran together unto Jerusalem the multitude also of the cities adjoining, bringing sick persons and such as were vexed of unclean spirits; who were all cured.
\v 17 And the high Priest rising up, and all that were with him, which is the heresy of the Sadducees, were replenished with zeal:
\v 18 laid hands upon the Apostles, and put them in the common prison.
\v 19 But an Angel of our Lord by night opening the gates of the prison, & leading them forth, said: \f + \fr 5:19 \ft An Angel leadeth them out of prison.\f*
\v 20 Go; and standing speak in the temple to the people all the words of this life.
\v 21 Who having heard this, early in the morning entered into the temple, and taught. And the high priest coming, and they that were with him, called together the Council & all the ancients of the children of Israel: and they sent to the prison that they might be brought.
\v 22 But when the ministers were come, and opening the prison, found them not; returning they told, saying:
\v 23 The prison truly we found shut with all diligence, and the keepers standing before the gates: but opening it, we found no man within.
\v 24 And as soon as the Magistrates of the temple and the chief Priests heard these words, they were in doubt of them, what would befall.
\v 25 And there came a certain man and told them: That the men, lo, which you did put in prison, are in the temple standing, and teaching the people.
\v 26 Then went the Magistrate with the ministers, & brought them without force, for they feared the people, lest they should be stoned.
\v 27 And when they had brought them, they set them in the Council. And the high Priest asked them,
\v 28 saying: Commanding we commanded you that you should not teach in this name: and behold you have filled Jerusalem with your doctrine, and you will bring upon us the blood of this man. \x + \xo 5:28 \xt Act. 4, 18.\x*
\v 29 But Peter answering and the Apostles, said: God must be obeyed, rather than men.
\v 30 The God of our Fathers hath raised up \sc Jesus\sc*, whom you did kill, hanging him upon a tree.
\v 31 This Prince and Saviour God hath exalted with his right hand, to give repentance to Israel, and remission of sins.
\v 32 And we are witnesses of these words, and the Holy Ghost, whom God hath given to all that obey him.
\v 33 When they had heard these things, it cut them to the heart, and they consulted to kill them.
\v 34 But one in the Council rising up, a Pharisee named Gamaliel, a Doctor of law honourable to all the people, commanded the men to be put forth a while.
\v 35 and he said to them: Ye men of Israel, take heed to yourselves touching these men what you mean to do.
\v 36 For before these days there rose Theodas, saying he was somebody, to whom consented a number of men about four hundred, who was slain: and all that believed him, were dispersed, and brought to nothing. \f + \fr 5:36 \ft Theudas\f*
\v 37 After this fellow there rose Judas of Galilee in the days of the Enrolling, and drew away the people after him, and he perished: and as many as ever consented to him, were dispersed.
\v 38 And now therefore I say to you, depart from these men and let them alone: for if this counsel or work be of men, it will be dissolved:
\v 39 but if it be of God, you are not able to dissolve <alt>them</alt>, lest perhaps you be found to resist God also. And they consented to him. \f + \fr 5:39 \ft Time, and the evident success of Christ's Church and religion, prove it to be of God: no violence of the Jews, no persecution of the Heathen Princes, no endeavour of domestical Adversaries, heretics, Schismatics, or ill livers, prevailing against it; as on the other side, many attempts have been made by Arius, Macedonius, Nestorius, Luther, and the like, who thought themselves somebody: but after they had played their parts a while, their memory is buried, or liveth only in malediction & infamy, and their scholars come to naught. Therefore let no Cath. man be scandalized that this heresy holdeth up for a time. For the Arians & some others flourished much longer than these, and were better supported by Princes and learning, & yet had an end.\f* \f + \fr 5:39 \ft it\f*
\v 40 And calling in the Apostles, after they had scourged them, they charged them that they should not speak in the name of \sc Jesus\sc*, and dismissed them.
\v 41 And they went from the sight of the Council rejoicing, because they were accounted worthy to suffer reproach for the name of \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 42 And every day they ceased not in the temple, and from house to house to teach and evangelize Christ \sc Jesus\sc*.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* in those days the number of Disciples increasing, there arose a murmuring of the Greeks against the Hebrews, for that their widows were despised in the daily ministry.
\v 2 And the Twelve calling together the multitude of the Disciples, said: it is not reason, that we leave the word of God, and serve tables.
\v 3 Consider therefore brethren, seven men of you of good testimony, full of the Holy Ghost and wisdom, whom we may appoint over this business.
\v 4 But we will be instant in prayer and the ministry of the word.
\v 5 And the saying was liked before all the multitude. And they chose Steven a man full of faith and of the Holy Ghost, and Philippe, and Prochorus, and Nicanor, and Timon, and Parmenas, and Nicolas a stranger of Antioch: \f + \fr 6:5 \ft The election of the 7 first Deacons.\f* \f + \fr 6:5 \ft c προσήλυτον.\f*
\v 6 These they did set in the presence of the Apostles: and praying they imposed hands upon them. \f + \fr 6:6 \ft Order of Deacons given by imposition of hands. See Annot. Act. 13, 3.\f*
\v 7 And the word of God increased, and the number of the Disciples was multiplied in Jerusalem exceedingly: a great multitude also of the Priests obeyed the faith. \f + \fr 6:7 \ft Now also the Priests and they of greater knowledge and estimation began to believe.\f*
\v 8 And Steven full of grace and fortitude did great wonders & signs among the people. \f + \fr 6:8 \ft b The Epistle upon S. Steven's day in Christmas. And his Invention Aug. 3.\f*
\v 9 And there arose certain of that which is called the Synagogue of the Libertines, and of the Cyrenians, and of the Alexandrians, and of them that were of Cilicia and Asia, disputing with Steven:
\v 10 and they could not resist the wisdom and the Spirit that spake.
\v 11 Then they suborned men, to say they had heard him speak words of blasphemy against Moyses and God.
\v 12 They therefore stirred up the people, and the Ancients, and the Scribes: and running together they took him, and brought him into the Council,
\v 13 and they set false witnesses that said: This man ceaseth not to speak words against the holy place & the Law.
\v 14 For we have heard him say, that this same \sc Jesus\sc* of Nazareth shall destroy this place, and shall change the traditions, which Moyses delivered unto us.
\v 15 And all that sat in the Council beholding him, saw his face as it were the face of an Angel. \f + \fr 6:15 \ft Such is the face of all constant & cheerful Martyrs, to their persecutors and judges.\f*
\c 7
\p
\v 0 mad, so that they stone him to death (Saul consenting) \add he commending his soul to \sc Jesus\sc*, and humbly praying for them.\add*
\v 1 \sc And\sc* the chief priest said: Are these things so?
\v 2 Who said: Ye men, brethren and fathers, hear. The God of glory appeared to our father Abraham when he was in Mesopotamia, before that he abode in Charan,
\v 3 & said to him: \add Go forth out of thy country, and out of thy kindred, & come into a land that I shall shew thee.\add* \x + \xo 7:3 \xt Gen. 12, 1.\x*
\v 4 Then went he forth out of the land of the Chaldees, and dwelt in Charan. And from thence, after his father was dead, he translated him into this land wherein you do now dwell.
\v 5 And he gave him no inheritance in it, no not the pace of a foot: and he promised to give it him in possession, and to his seed after him, when as he had no child.
\v 6 And God spake to him: \add That his seed shall be a sojourner in a strange country, and they shall subdue them to servitude, and shall evil entreat them four hundred years.\add* \x + \xo 7:6 \xt Gen. 15, 13.\x*
\v 7 \add and the nation which they shall serve, will I judge,\add* said God. \add And after these things they shall go forth and \add* \add shall serve me in this place.\add* \f + \fr 7:7 \ft c λατρεύσουσι.\f*
\v 8 And he gave him the testament of circumcision, and so he begat Isaac, and circumcised him the eighth day: and Isaac, Jacob: and Jacob, the twelve Patriarchs. \x + \xo 7:8 \xt Gen. 17.\x* \x + \xo 7:8 \xt Gen. 21.\x* \x + \xo 7:8 \xt Gen. 25.\x* \x + \xo 7:8 \xt Gen. 29, 30. 35.\x*
\v 9 And the Patriarchs through emulation, sold Joseph into Ægypt. And God was with him: \x + \xo 7:9 \xt Gen. 37.\x*
\v 10 and delivered him out of all his tribulations. And he gave him grace and wisdom in the sight of Pharao the king of Ægypt, and he appointed him Governor over Ægypt and over all his house. \x + \xo 7:10 \xt Gen. 41.\x*
\v 11 And there came famine upon all Ægypt and Chanaan, and great tribulation: and our fathers found no victuals.
\v 12 But when Jacob had heard that there was corn in Ægypt; he sent our fathers first: \x + \xo 7:12 \xt Gen. 42.\x*
\v 13 and at the second time Joseph was known of his brethren, and his kindred was made known unto Pharao. \x + \xo 7:13 \xt Gen. 45.\x*
\v 14 And Joseph sending, called thither Jacob his father and all his kindred in seventy five souls.
\v 15 And Jacob descended into Ægypt: and he died, and our fathers. \x + \xo 7:15 \xt Gen. 46.\x* \x + \xo 7:15 \xt Gen. 49. Gen. 50.\x*
\v 16 And they were translated into Sichem, and were laid in the sepulchre that Abraham bought for a price of silver of the sons of Hemor the son of Sichem. \f + \fr 7:16 \ft Translation of Saints' bodies agreeable to nature & Scripture. And the desire to be buried in one place more than another (which the holy Patriarchs also had Gen. 49, 29. 50, 24. Hebr. 11, 22. ) hath sometime great causes. Aug. de Cur. pro mort. c. 1. & ult.\f* \x + \xo 7:16 \xt Gen. 23.\x* \x + \xo 7:16 \xt Ios. 24.\x*
\v 17 And when the time drew near of the promise which God had promised to Abraham, the people increased and was multiplied in Ægypt, \x + \xo 7:17 \xt Exo. 1, 7.\x*
\v 18 until another king arose in Ægypt, that knew not Joseph.
\v 19 This same circumventing our stock, afflicted our fathers, that they should expose their children, to the end they might not be kept alive.
\v 20 The same time was Moyses born, and he was acceptable to God; who was nourished three months in his father's house. \x + \xo 7:20 \xt Exo. 2, 2.\x*
\v 21 And when he was exposed, Pharao's daughter took him up, and nourished him for her own son.
\v 22 And Moyses was instructed in all the wisdom of the Ægyptians: and he was mighty in his words and works.
\v 23 And when he was fully of the age of forty years, it came to his mind to visit his brethren the children of Israel. \x + \xo 7:23 \xt Exo. 2, 11.\x*
\v 24 And when he had seen one suffer wrong, he defended him: and striking the Ægyptian, he revenged his quarrel that sustained the wrong.
\v 25 And he thought that his brethren did understand that God by his hand would save them: but they understood it not.
\v 26 And the day following he appeared to them being at strife: and he reconciled them unto peace, saying: Men, ye are brethren, wherefore hurt you one another? \x + \xo 7:26 \xt Exo. 2, 13.\x*
\v 27 But he that did the injury to his neighbour, repelled him, saying: \add Who hath appointed thee prince and judge over us:\add*
\v 28 \add What, wilt thou kill me, as thou didst yesterday kill the Ægyptian?\add*
\v 29 And Moyses fled upon this word: and he became a sojourner in the land of Madian, where he begat two sons.
\v 30 And after forty years were expired, there appeared to him in the desert of mount Sina an Angel in the fire of the flame of a bush. \x + \xo 7:30 \xt Exo. 3, 2.\x*
\v 31 And Moyses seeing it, marveled at the vision. And as he went near to view it, the voice of our Lord was made to him:
\v 32 \add I am the God of thy fathers; the God of Abraham, the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob.\add* And Moyses being made to tremble, durst not view it.
\v 33 And our Lord said to him: \add Loose off the shoe of thy feet, for the place wherein thou standest, is holy ground.\add*
\v 34 \add Seeing I have seen the affliction of my people which is in Ægypt, and I have heard their groaning and am descended to deliver them. And now come, and I will send thee into Ægypt.\add*
\v 35 This Moyses, whom they denied, saying: \add Who hath appointed thee prince and Captain?\add* him God sent prince & redeemer with the hand of the Angel that appeared to him in the bush. \f + \fr 7:35 \ft Christ is our Redeemer, and yet Moyses is here called redeemer. So Christ is our Mediator and Advocate, and yet we may have Saints our inferior mediators and advocates also. See Annot. 1. Io. 2, 1.\f*
\v 36 He brought them forth doing wonders and signs in the land of Ægypt, and in the red sea, and in the desert forty years. \x + \xo 7:36 \xt Exo. 7. 8. 9. 10. 11. 12, 37.\x* \x + \xo 7:36 \xt Exo. 16.\x*
\v 37 This is that Moyses which said to the children of Israel: \add A Prophet will God raise up to you of your own brethren as myself: him you shall hear.\add* \x + \xo 7:37 \xt Deu. 18.\x*
\v 38 This is he that was in the assembly in the wilderness, with the Angel that spake to him in Mount Sina, and with our fathers: who received the words of life to give unto us. \x + \xo 7:38 \xt Exo. 19, 3. 19.\x*
\v 39 To whom our fathers would not be obedient: but they repelled him, and in their hearts turned away into Ægypt,
\v 40 saying to Aaron: \add Make us gods that may go before us. For this Moyses that brought us out of the land of Ægypt, we know not what is befallen to him.\add* \x + \xo 7:40 \xt Exo. 32, 1.\x*
\v 41 And they made a calf in those days, and offered sacrifice to the idol, and rejoiced in the works of their own hands.
\v 42 And God turned, and delivered them up to serve the host of Heaven, as it is written in the book of the Prophets: \add Did you offer victims and hosts unto me forty years in the desert, O house of Israel?\add* \f + \fr 7:42 \ft For a just punishment of their former offences God gave them up to work what wickedness they would themselves, as it is said of the Gentiles Rom. 1.\f* \f + \fr 7:42 \ft c λατρεύειν.\f* \x + \xo 7:42 \xt Amos. 5, 25.\x*
\v 43 \add And you took unto you the tabernacle of Moloch, and the star of your god Rempham, figures which you made, to adore them. And I will translate you beyond Babylon.\add*
\v 44 The tabernacle of testimony was among our fathers in the desert, as God ordained speaking to Moyses, \add that he should make it according to the form which he had seen.\add* \x + \xo 7:44 \xt Exo. 25, 40.\x*
\v 45 Which our fathers with Jesus receiving, brought it in also into the possession of the Gentiles. Which God expelled from the face of our fathers, till in the days of David, \f + \fr 7:45 \ft c This is Josue, so called in Greek in type of our Saviour.\f* \x + \xo 7:45 \xt Ios. 3, 14.\x*
\v 46 who found grace before God, and desired that he might find a tabernacle for the God of Jacob. \x + \xo 7:46 \xt Ps. 131, 5.\x*
\v 47 And Salomon built him a house. \x + \xo 7:47 \xt 1. Par. 17.\x*
\v 48 But the Highest dwelleth not in houses made by hand, as the Prophet saith: \x + \xo 7:48 \xt Act. 17. 25.\x*
\v 49 \add Heaven is my seat: and the earth the foot-stool of my feet. What house will you build me, saith our Lord, or what place is there of my resting?\add* \x + \xo 7:49 \xt Esa. 66, 1.\x*
\v 50 \add Hath not my hand made all these things?\add*
\v 51 You stiff-necked and of uncircumcised hearts and ears, you always resist the Holy Ghost: as your fathers, yourselves also.
\v 52 Which of the Prophets did not your fathers persecute? And they slew them that foretold of the coming of the Just one, of whom now
\v 53 you have been betrayers and murderers: who received the Law by the disposition of Angels, and have not kept it.
\v 54 And hearing these things they were cut in their hearts, and they gnashed with their teeth at him.
\v 55 But he being full of the Holy Ghost, looking steadfastly unto Heaven, saw the glory of God, and \sc Jesus\sc* standing on the right hand of God. And he said: Behold I see the Heavens opened, and the Son of man standing on the right hand of God. \f + \fr 7:55 \ft c The comfort of all Martyrs.\f*
\v 56 And they crying out with a loud voice, stopped their ears, and with one accord ran violently upon him.
\v 57 And casting him forth without the city they stoned him: and the witnesses laid off their garments beside the feet of a young man that was called Saul. \x + \xo 7:57 \xt Act. 22, 20.\x*
\v 58 And they stoned Steven invocating, and saying: Lord \sc Jesus\sc*, receive my spirit.
\v 59 And falling on his knees, he cried with a loud voice, saying: Lord, lay not this sin unto them. And when he had said this, he fell asleep. And Saul was consenting to his death. \f + \fr 7:59 \ft Eusebius Emissenus saith, when he prayeth for his persecutors, he promiseth to his worshippers his manifest intercession & suffrages. in ho. S. Steph. & S. Augustine, Si Stephanus sic non orasset, Ecclesia Paulum non haberet. Serm. 1. de S. Stephano.\f*
\c 8
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* the same day there was made a great persecution in the Church, which was at Jerusalem, and all were dispersed through the countries of Jewry and Samaria, saving the Apostles.
\v 2 And devout men took order for Steven's funeral, and made great mourning upon him. \f + \fr 8:2 \ft c curaverunt συνεκόμισαν\f*
\v 3 But Saul wasted the Church: entering in from house to house, and drawing men and women, delivered them into prison. \x + \xo 8:3 \xt Act. 22, 4.\x*
\v 4 They therefore that were dispersed, passed through, evangelizing the word. \f + \fr 8:4 \ft This persecution wrought much good, being an occasion that the dispersed preached Christ in diverse Countries where they came.\f*
\v 5 And Philippe descending into the city of Samaria, preached \sc Christ\sc* unto them. \f + \fr 8:5 \ft The Epistle upon Thursday in Whitsunweek.\f*
\v 6 and the multitudes were attent to those things which were said of Philippe, with one accord hearing, and seeing the signs that he did.
\v 7 For many of them that had unclean spirits, crying with a loud voice, went out. And many sick of the palsy and lame were cured.
\v 8 There was made therefore great joy in that city.
\v 9 And a certain man named Simon, who before had been in that city a Magician, seducing the nation of Samaria, saying himself to be some great one:
\v 10 unto whom all harkened from the least to the greatest, saying: This man is the power of God, that is called great.
\v 11 And they were attent upon him, because a long time he had bewitched them with his magical practices.
\v 12 But when they had believed Philippe evangelizing of the Kingdom of God, and of the name of \sc Jesus Christ\sc*, they were baptized, men and women.
\v 13 Then Simon also himself believed: & being baptized, he cleaved to Philippe. Seeing also signs and very great miracles to be done, he was astonished with admiration.
\v 14 And when the Apostles who were in Jerusalem, had heard that Samaria had received the word of God: they sent unto them Peter and John. \f + \fr 8:14 \ft The Epistle upon Tuesday in Whitsunweek. And in a votive of the Holy Ghost.\f* \f + \fr 8:14 \ft Sæpe sibi socium Petrus facit esse Ioannem: Ecclesiæ quia virgo placet. Peter often maketh John his companion, because the Church loveth a virgin. Arator apud Bedam in Act.\f*
\v 15 Who when they were come, prayed for them, that they might receive the Holy Ghost.
\v 16 For he was not yet come upon any of them, but they were only baptized in the name of our Lord \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 17 Then did they impose their hands upon them, & they received the Holy Ghost.
\v 18 And when Simon had seen that by the imposition of the hand of the Apostles, the Holy Ghost was given, he offered them money,
\v 19 saying: Give me also this power, that on whomsoever I impose my hands, he may receive the Holy Ghost.
\v 20 But Peter said to him: Thy money be with thee unto perdition: because thou hast thought that the gift of God is purchased with money.
\v 21 Thou hast no part, nor lot in this word. For thy heart is not right before God.
\v 22 Do penance therefore from this thy wickedness: and pray to God, if perhaps this cogitation of thy heart may be remitted thee. \f + \fr 8:22 \ft c μετανόησον ἀπὸ See Apocal. 9, 21.\f*
\v 23 For I see thou art in the gall of bitterness and the obligation of iniquity.
\v 24 And Simon answering said: Pray you for me to our Lord, that nothing come upon me of these things which you have said.
\v 25 And they indeed having testified and spoken the word of our Lord, returned to Jerusalem, and evangelized to many countries of the Samaritans.
\v 26 And an Angel of our Lord spake to Philippe, saying: Arise, and go toward the South, to the way that goeth down from Jerusalem into Gaza: this is desert. \f + \fr 8:26 \ft b The Epistle upon Thursday in Easter week.\f*
\v 27 And rising he went. And behold, a man of Æthiopia, an Eunuch, of great authority under Candace the queen of the Æthiopians, who was over all her treasures, was come to Jerusalem to adore: \f + \fr 8:27 \ft Note that this Æthiopian came to Hierusalem to adore, that is, on Pilgrimage. Whereby we may learn that it is an acceptable act of religion to go from home to places of greater devotion & sanctification.\f*
\v 28 and he was returning and sitting upon his chariot, and reading Esay the Prophet.
\v 29 And the Spirit said to Philippe: Go near, and join thyself to this same chariot.
\v 30 And Philippe running thereunto, heard him reading Esay the Prophet, and he said: Trowest thou that thou understandest the things which thou readest?
\v 31 Who said: And how can I, unless some man shew me? & he desired Philippe that he would come up and sit with him. \f + \fr 8:31 \ft The Scriptures are so written that they cannot be understood without an interpreter, as easy as our Protestants make them. See S. Hierom Ep. ad Paulinum de omnibus divinæ historiæ libris, set in the beginning of Latin Bibles.\f*
\v 32 And the place of the scripture which he did read, was this: \add As a sheep to slaughter was he led: and as a lamb before his shearer, without voice, so did he not open his mouth.\add* \x + \xo 8:32 \xt Es. 53, 7.\x*
\v 33 \add In humility his judgement was taken away. His generation who shall declare, for from the earth shall his life be taken?\add*
\v 34 And the Eunuch answering Philip, said: I beseech thee, of whom doth the Prophet speak this? of himself, or of some other?
\v 35 And, Philip opening his mouth, and beginning from this scripture, evangelized unto him \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 36 And as they went by the way, they came to a certain water: and the Eunuch said: Lo water, <alt>who</alt> doth let me to be baptized? \f + \fr 8:36 \ft what\f*
\v 37 And Philip said: If thou believe with all thy heart, thou mayest. And he answering said: I believe that \sc Jesus Christ\sc* is the Son of God.
\v 38 And he commanded the chariot to stay: and both went down into the water, Philip and the Eunuch, and he baptized him.
\v 39 And when they were come up out of the water, the Spirit of our Lord took away Philip, & the Eunuch saw him no more. And he went on his way rejoicing.
\v 40 But Philip was found in Azotus, and passing through, he evangelized to all the cities, till he came to Cæsarea.
\c 9
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* Saul as yet breathing forth threatenings and slaughter against the Disciples of our Lord, came to the high priest, \f + \fr 9:1 \ft The Epistle upon the Conversion of S. Paul Ian. 25.\f* \x + \xo 9:1 \xt Act. 22, 4. Gal. 1, 13.\x*
\v 2 and asked letters of him unto Damascus to the Synagogues that if he had found any men and women of this way, he might bring them bound unto Jerusalem.
\v 3 And as he went on his journey, it chanced that he drew nigh to Damascus: and suddenly a light from Heaven shined round about him. \x + \xo 9:3 \xt 1. Cor. 15, 8.\x*
\v 4 And falling on the ground, he heard a voice saying to him, Saul, Saul why persecutest thou me? \f + \fr 9:4 \ft The heretics that conclude CHRIST so in heaven that he can be no where else till the day of Judgement, shall hardly resolve a man that would know where CHRIST was when he appeared here in the way, and spake these words to Saul.\f*
\v 5 Who said: Who art thou Lord? And he: I am \sc Jesus\sc* whom thou doest persecute. It is hard for thee to kick against the prick.
\v 6 And trembling and being astonished he said: Lord, what wilt thou have me to do?
\v 7 And our Lord to him: Arise and go into the city, & it shall be told thee what thou must do. But the men that went in company with him, stood amazed, hearing the voice, but seeing no man.
\v 8 And Saul rose up from the ground, and his eyes being opened, he saw nothing. And they drawing him by the hands, brought him into Damascus.
\v 9 And he was there three days not seeing, and he did neither eat nor drink.
\v 10 And there was a certain Disciple at Damascus, named Ananias: and our Lord said to him in a vision, Ananias. But he said, Lo, here I am Lord.
\v 11 And our Lord to him: Arise, and go into the street that is called Straight: and seek in the house of Judas, one named Saul of Tarsus. For behold he prayeth.
\v 12 (And he saw a man named Ananias, coming in and imposing hands upon him for to receive his sight.)
\v 13 But Ananias answered: Lord, I have heard by many of this man, how much evil he hath done to thy saints in Jerusalem:
\v 14 and here he hath authority from the chief priests to bind all that invocate thy name.
\v 15 And our Lord said to him: Go, for a vessel of election is this man unto me, to carry my name before the Gentiles, and kings, and the children of Israel.
\v 16 For I will shew him how great things he must suffer for my name.
\v 17 And Ananias went, and entered into the house: and imposing hands upon him, he said: Brother Saul, our Lord \sc Jesus\sc* hath sent me, he that appeared to thee in the way that thou camest; that thou mayest see and be filled with the Holy Ghost.
\v 18 And forthwith there fell from his eyes as it were scales, and he received sight: and rising he was baptized. \f + \fr 9:18 \ft Paul also himself, though with the divine and heavenly voice prostrated and instructed, yet was sent to a man to receive the Sacraments, & to be joined to the Church. August. de doct. Chr. lib. 1. in prooem.\f*
\v 19 And when he had taken meat, he was strengthened. And he was with the Disciples that were at Damascus, for certain days.
\v 20 And incontinent entering into the Synagogues, <alt>he</alt> preached \sc Jesus\sc*, that this is the Son of God. \f + \fr 9:20 \ft in the Synagogues he.\f*
\v 21 And all that heard, were astonished, and said: Is not this he that expugned in Jerusalem those that invocated this name; and came hither to this purpose that he might bring them bound to the chief priests?
\v 22 But Saul waxed mighty much more and confounded the Jews that dwelt at Damascus, affirming that this is \sc Christ\sc*.
\v 23 And when many days were passed, the Jews consulted that they might kill him.
\v 24 But their conspiracy came to Saul's knowledge. And they kept the gates also day and night, that they might kill him. \x + \xo 9:24 \xt 2. Cor. 11, 32.\x*
\v 25 But the Disciples taking him in the night, conveyed him away by the wall, letting him down in a basket.
\v 26 And when he was come into Jerusalem, he assayed to join himself to the Disciples, & all feared him, not believing that he was a Disciple.
\v 27 But Barnabas took him & brought him to the Apostles, and told them how in the way he had seen our Lord, and that he spake unto him, & how in Damascus he dealt confidently in the name of \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 28 And he was with them going in & going out in Jerusalem, & dealing confidently in the name of our Lord.
\v 29 He spake also to the Gentiles, & disputed with the Greeks: but they sought to kill him.
\v 30 Which when the brethren had known, they brought him down to Cæsarea & sent him away to Tarsus.
\v 31 The \sc Church\sc* truly through all Jewry & Galilee and Samaria had peace, & was edified, walking in the fear of our Lord, and was replenished with the consolation of the Holy Ghost. \f + \fr 9:31 \ft The Church visibly proceedeth still with much comfort & manifold increase even by persecution.\f*
\v 32 And it came to pass, that Peter as he passed through all, came to the saints that dwelt at Lydda.
\v 33 and he found there a certain man named Æneas, lying in his bed from eight years before, who had the palsy.
\v 34 And Peter said to him: Æneas, our Lord \sc Jesus Christ\sc* <alt>heal</alt> thee: arise, and make thy bed. And incontinent he arose. \f + \fr 9:34 \ft healeth\f*
\v 35 And all that dwelt at Lydda and Sarona, saw him: who converted to our Lord.
\v 36 And in Joppe there was a certain Disciple named Tabitha, which by interpretation is called Dorcas. This woman was full of good works & alms-deeds which she did. \f + \fr 9:36 \ft Behold good works and alms-deeds, & the force thereof reaching even to the next life.\f*
\v 37 And it came to pass in those days, that she was sick and died. Whom when they had washed, they laid her in an upper chamber.
\v 38 And whereas Lydda was nigh to Joppe, the Disciples hearing that Peter was in it, they sent two men unto him, desiring him: Be not loath to come so far as to us.
\v 39 And Peter rising up came with them. And when he was come, they brought him into the upper chamber: and all the widows stood about him weeping, and shewing him the coats and garments which Dorcas made them. \f + \fr 9:39 \ft The prayers of our Almsfolk & beadsmen may do us great good even after our departure. For if they procured her temporal life, much more may they help us to God's mercy and to release of punishment in Purgatory.\f*
\v 40 And all being put forth, Peter falling on his knees prayed, and turning to the body he said: Tabitha, arise. And she opened her eyes: and seeing Peter, she sat up.
\v 41 And giving her his hand, he lifted her up. And when he had called the saints and the widows, he presented her alive.
\v 42 And it was made known throughout all Joppe: and many believed in our Lord.
\v 43 And it came to pass that he abode many days in Joppe, with one Simon a tanner.
\c 10
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* there was a certain man in Cæsarea, named Cornelius, Centurion of that which is called the Italian band,
\v 2 religious, & fearing God with all his house, doing many alms-deeds to the people. And always praying to God,
\v 3 he saw in a vision manifestly, about the ninth hour of the day, an Angel of God coming in unto him and saying to him: Cornelius.
\v 4 But he beholding him, taken with fear, said: Who art thou Lord? And he said to him: Thy prayers and thy alms-deeds are ascended into remembrance in the sight of God.
\v 5 And now send men unto Joppe, and call hither one Simon that is surnamed Peter.
\v 6 He lodgeth with one Simon a tanner, whose house is by the sea side. He will tell thee what thou must do.
\v 7 And when the Angel was departed that spake to him, he called two of his household, and a soldier that feared our Lord, of them that were under him.
\v 8 To whom when he had told all, he sent them unto Joppe.
\v 9 And the next day whiles they were going on their journey, and drawing nigh to the city, Peter went up into the higher parts, to pray about the sixth hour.
\v 10 And being hungry, he was desirous to take somewhat. And as they were preparing, there fell upon him an excess of mind:
\v 11 and he saw the Heaven opened, and a certain vessel descending, as it were a great linen sheet with four corners let down from Heaven to the earth,
\v 12 wherein were all four-footed beasts, and that creep on the earth, and fowls of the air.
\v 13 And there came a voice to him: Arise Peter, kill, and eat.
\v 14 But Peter said: God forbid, Lord; for I did never eat any common and unclean thing.
\v 15 And a voice came to him again the second time: That which God hath purified, do not thou call common. \f + \fr 10:15 \ft Here God first uttered to Peter that the time was come to preach also to the Gentiles, and to converse with them for their salvation, no less than with the Jews, with full freedom to eat all meats without respect of the prohibition of certain, made in the old Law.\f*
\v 16 And this was done thrice, & forthwith the vessel was taken up again into Heaven.
\v 17 And whiles Peter doubted within himself, what the vision should be that he had seen, behold the men that were sent from Cornelius, inquiring for Simon's house, stood at the gate.
\v 18 And when they had called, they asked, if Simon that is surnamed Peter were lodged there.
\v 19 And as Peter was thinking of the vision, the Spirit said to him: Behold, three men do seek thee.
\v 20 Arise therefore, and get thee down, and go with them, doubting nothing; for I have sent them.
\v 21 And Peter going down to the men, said: Behold I am he whom you seek; what is the cause, for the which you are come?
\v 22 Who said: Cornelius the Centurion, a just man and that feareth God, and having testimony of all the nation of the Jews, received an answer of an holy Angel to send for thee into his house, and to hear words of thee.
\v 23 Therefore bringing them in, he lodged them. And the day following he arose and went with them: and certain of the brethren of Joppe accompanied him.
\v 24 And on the morrow he entered into Cæsarea. And Cornelius expected them, having called together his kin, and special friends.
\v 25 And it came to pass, when Peter was come in, Cornelius came to meet him, & falling at his feet adored.
\v 26 But Peter lifted him up saying: Arise, myself also am a man.
\v 27 And talking with him, he went in, and findeth many that were assembled.
\v 28 And he said to them: You know how abominable it is for a man that is a Jew, to join, or to approach unto a stranger: but God hath shewed to me, to call no man common or unclean.
\v 29 For the which cause, making no doubt, I came when I was sent for. I demand therefore, for what cause you have sent for me?
\v 30 And Cornelius said: Four days since, until this hour, I was praying the ninth hour in my house, and behold a man stood before me in white apparel, \f + \fr 10:30 \ft c At the time of prayer specially God sendeth men comfortable visitations.\f* \f + \fr 10:30 \ft c In the Greek, fasting & praying.\f* \f + \fr 10:30 \ft Note these apparitions and visions to S. Peter, Cornelius, and others, in the Scriptures very often, against the incredulity of our Heretics, that will believe neither vision nor miracle, not expressed in Scripture: these being believed of Christian men even before they were written.\f*
\v 31 and said: Cornelius, thy prayer is heard, and thy alms-deeds are in memory in the sight of God.
\v 32 Send therefore to Joppe, and call hither Simon that is surnamed Peter: he lodgeth in the house of Simon a tanner by the sea side.
\v 33 Immediately therefore I sent to thee: and thou hast done well in coming. Now therefore all we are present in thy sight, to hear all things whatsoever are commanded thee of the Lord.
\v 34 And Peter opening his mouth, said: In very deed I perceive that God is not an accepter of persons.
\v 35 But in every nation, he that feareth him, and worketh justice, is acceptable to him. \f + \fr 10:35 \ft c Not such as believe only, but such as fear God and work justice, are acceptable to him.\f*
\v 36 The word did God send to the children of Israel, preaching peace by \sc Jesus Christ\sc* (this is Lord of all.)
\v 37 You know the word that hath been made through all Jewry, for beginning from Galilee, after the baptism which John preached: \f + \fr 10:37 \ft b The Epistle upon Monday in Easter week.\f* \x + \xo 10:37 \xt Mat. 4, 12.\x*
\v 38 \sc Jesus\sc* of Nazareth how God anointed him with the Holy Ghost and with power, who went throughout doing good and healing all that were oppressed of the devil, because God was with him.
\v 39 And we are witnesses of all things that he did in the country of the Jews and in Jerusalem, whom they killed hanging him upon a tree.
\v 40 Him God raised up the third day and gave him to be made manifest,
\v 41 not to all the people, but to us, who did eat and drink with him after he rose again from the dead.
\v 42 And he commanded us to preach to the people, & to testify that it is he that of God was appointed judge of the living and of the dead. \f + \fr 10:42 \ft The Epistle upon Monday in Whitsunweek.\f*
\v 43 To him all the prophets give testimony, that all receive remission of sins by his name, which believe in him.
\v 44 As Peter was yet speaking these words, the Holy Ghost fell upon all that heard the word.
\v 45 And the faithful of the Circumcision that came with Peter, were astonished, for that the grace of the Holy Ghost was poured out upon the Gentiles also.
\v 46 For they heard them speaking with tongues, and magnifying God.
\v 47 Then Peter answered: Can any man forbid water, that these should not be baptized which have received the Holy Ghost as well as we?
\v 48 And he commanded them to be baptized in the name of our Lord \sc Jesus Christ\sc*. Then they desired him that he would tarry with them certain days.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* the Apostles and brethren that were in Jewry, heard that the Gentiles also received the word of God.
\v 2 And when Peter was come up to Jerusalem, they that were of the Circumcision reasoned against him, saying:
\v 3 Why didst thou enter in to men uncircumcised, and didst eat with them? \f + \fr 11:3 \ft c præputium habentes.\f*
\v 4 But Peter began and declared to them the order, saying:
\v 5 I was in the city of Joppe praying, & I saw in an excess of mind a vision, a certain vessel descending as it were a great sheet with four corners let down from heaven, & it came even unto me. \x + \xo 11:5 \xt Act. 10, 9.\x*
\v 6 Into which I looking considered, & saw four footed beasts of the earth, & cattle, & such as creep, & fowls of the air.
\v 7 And I heard also a voice saying to me: Arise Peter, kill and eat.
\v 8 And I said: Not so Lord; for common or unclean thing never entered into my mouth.
\v 9 And a voice answered the second time from heaven: That which God hath made clean, do not thou call common.
\v 10 And this was done thrice: and all were taken up again into heaven.
\v 11 And behold, three men immediately were come to the house wherein I was, sent to me from Cæsarea.
\v 12 And the spirit said to me, that I should go with them, doubting nothing. And there came with me these six brethren also: and we went into the man's house.
\v 13 And he told us, how he had seen an Angel in his house, standing and saying to him: Send to Joppe, and call hither Simon, that is surnamed Peter,
\v 14 who shall speak to thee words wherein thou shalt be saved and all thy house.
\v 15 And when I had begun to speak, the Holy Ghost fell upon them, as upon us also in the beginning.
\v 16 And I remembered the word of our Lord, according as he said: \add John indeed baptized with water, but you shall be baptized with the Holy Ghost.\add* \x + \xo 11:16 \xt Act. 1, 5.\x*
\v 17 If therefore God hath given them the same grace, as to us also that believed in our Lord \sc Jesus Christ\sc*: who was I that might prohibit God?
\v 18 Having heard these things, they held their peace: & glorified God, saying: God then to the Gentiles also hath given repentance unto life. \f + \fr 11:18 \ft Good Christians hear and obey gladly such truths as be opened unto them from God by their chief Pastors, by vision, revelation, or otherwise.\f*
\v 19 And they truly that had been dispersed by the tribulation that was made under Steven, walked throughout unto Phoenice & Cypres & Antioch, speaking the word to none, but to the Jews only. \x + \xo 11:19 \xt Act. 8, 1.\x*
\v 20 But certain of them were men of Cypres and Cyrene, who when they were entered into Antioch, spake to the Greeks, preaching our Lord \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 21 And the hand of our Lord was with them: and a great number of believers was converted to our Lord. \f + \fr 11:21 \ft The Epistle upon S. Barnabee's day. Iun. 11.\f*
\v 22 And the report came to the ears of the Church that was at Jerusalem, touching these things: and they sent Barnabas as far as Antioch. \x + \xo 11:22 \xt Act. 4, 36.\x*
\v 23 Who when he was come, and saw the grace of God, rejoiced: and he exhorted all with purpose of heart to continue in our Lord:
\v 24 because he was a good man, and full of the Holy Ghost and faith. And a great multitude was added to our Lord.
\v 25 And he went forth to Tarsus, to seek Saul: \x + \xo 11:25 \xt Act. 9, 30.\x*
\v 26 whom when he had found, he brought him to Antioch. And they conversed there in the church a whole year: and they taught a great multitude, so that the Disciples were at Antioch first named \sc Christians\sc*. \f + \fr 11:26 \ft The name of CHRISTIANS.\f*
\v 27 And in these days there came Prophets from Jerusalem to Antioch,
\v 28 and one of them rising, named Agabus, did by the Spirit signify a great famine that should be in the whole world, which fell under Claudius.
\v 29 And the Disciples according as each man had, purposed every one to send, for to serve the brethren that dwelt in Jewry:
\v 30 which also they did, sending to the ancients by the hands of Barnabas and Saul.
\c 12
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* at the same time Herod the king set his hands, to afflict certain of the Church. \f + \fr 12:1 \ft The Epistle upon SS. Peter and Paul's day Iun. 29.\f*
\v 2 And he killed James the brother of John with the sword.
\v 3 And seeing that it pleased the Jews, he added to apprehend Peter also. And it was the days of the Azymes.
\v 4 Whom when he had apprehended, he cast into prison, delivering him to four quaternions of soldiers to be kept, meaning after the Pasch to bring him forth to the people. \f + \fr 12:4 \ft As Peter's person was more notorious than others, & therefore better guarded than other, for fear he should escape; so God's providence in preserving & delivering him for the longer government of his Church, is very marvelous.\f*
\v 5 And Peter indeed was kept in prison. But prayer was made of the Church without intermission unto God for him.
\v 6 And when Herod would have brought him forth, the same night Peter was sleeping between two soldiers, bound with two chains: and the keepers before the door kept the prison.
\v 7 And behold an Angel of our Lord stood in presence: and light shined in the house: and striking Peter's side, he raised him, saying: Arise quickly. And the chains fell from his hands.
\v 8 And the Angel said to him: Gird thee, and put on thy shoes. And he did so. And he said to him: Put thy garment about thee, & follow me.
\v 9 And going forth he followed him, & he knew not that it was true which was done by the Angel: but he thought that he saw a vision.
\v 10 And passing through the first & the second watch, they came to the iron gate that leadeth to the city, which of itself opened to them. And going out, they went forward one street: and incontinent the Angel departed from him.
\v 11 And Peter returning to himself, said: Now I know in very deed that our Lord hath sent his Angel, and delivered me out of Herod's hand, & from all the expectation of the people of the Jews.
\v 12 And considering, he came to the house of Mary the mother of John, who was surnamed Mark, where many were gathered and praying. \f + \fr 12:12 \ft It is much for the praise of these good Christians that the assembly to God's service & prayer was kept in their houses in the time of persecution, & that the Apostle came thither straight out of prison, as his first refuge; as now Christian people do much to their commendation, in places where Heresy doth reign.\f*
\v 13 And when he knocked at the door of the gate, there came forth a wench to see, named Rhode.
\v 14 And as she knew Peter's voice, for joy she opened not the gate, but running in she told that Peter stood before the gate.
\v 15 But they said to her: Thou art mad. But she affirmed that it was so. But they said: It is his Angel.
\v 16 And Peter continued knocking. And when they had opened, they saw him, & were astonished.
\v 17 And beckoning with his hand to them, that they should hold their peace, he told how our Lord had brought him out of prison, & he said: Tell these things to James & to the brethren. And going forth he went into another place. \f + \fr 12:17 \ft Though God had so miraculously delivered him, yet he would not tempt God by tarrying among his persecutors, but according to Christ's commandment fled for a time.\f*
\v 18 And when day was come, there was no little ado between the soldiers, what was become of Peter.
\v 19 And Herod, when he had sought him, and had not found, making inquisition of the keepers, commanded them to be led away: & going down from Jewry into Cæsarea, there he abode.
\v 20 And he was angry with the Tyrians and the Sidonians. But they with one accord came to him, and persuading Blastus that was chief of the king's chamber, they desired peace, for that their countries were nourished by him.
\v 21 And upon a day appointed, Herod being arrayed with kingly attire, sat in the judgement seat, and made an oration to them.
\v 22 And the people made acclamation, The voices of a God, & not of a man.
\v 23 And forthwith an Angel of our Lord strook him, because he had not given the honour to God: and being consumed of worms, he gave up the ghost. \f + \fr 12:23 \ft Princes that take delight in the flattery and praises of the people, so much that they forget themselves to be men, & to give the honour to God, may be warned by this example.\f*
\v 24 But the word of our Lord increased and multiplied.
\v 25 And Barnabas and Saul returned from Jerusalem, having accomplished their ministry, taking with them John that was surnamed Mark. \x + \xo 12:25 \xt Act. 11, 29.\x*
\c 13
\p
\v 0 foretold by the Prophets. 44. But the next Sabboth, they \add blaspheming, he in plain terms forsaketh them, and turneth to the Gentiles. Whereat the Gentiles be as glad on the contrary side. 50. Finally the Jews raising persecution, they forsake them, pronouncing them to be obstinate contemners.\add* \f + \fr 13:0 \ft The 5. part. THE taking of the Gospel away from the obstinate Jews, and giving of it to the Gentiles, by the ministry of Paul and Barnabas.\f*
\v 1 \sc And\sc* there were in the Church which was at Antioch, Prophets and Doctors, among whom was Barnabas, and Simon that was called Niger, and Lucius of Cyrene, and Manahen who was the foster-brother of Herod the Tetrarch, and Saul.
\v 2 And as they were ministering to our Lord, & fasting, the Holy Ghost said: Separate me Saul and Barnabas unto the work, whereto I have taken them. \f + \fr 13:2 \ft c λειτουργούντων ἀυτῶν\f*
\v 3 Then they fasting and praying, and imposing hands upon them, dismissed them.
\v 4 And they being sent of the Holy Ghost, went to Seleucia, and thence sailed to Cypres.
\v 5 And when they were come to Salamina, they preached the word of God in the Synagogues of the Jews. And they had John also in their ministry.
\v 6 And when they had walked throughout the whole island as far as Paphos, they found a certain man that was a magician, a false-prophet, a Jew, whose name was <alt>Bar-iesu</alt>, \f + \fr 13:6 \ft Barieu\f*
\v 7 who was with the Proconsul Sergius Paulus a wise man. He sending for Barnabas & Saul, desired to hear the word of God.
\v 8 But Elymas the magician (for so is his name interpreted) resisted them, seeking to avert the Proconsul from the faith.
\v 9 But Saul, otherwise Paul, replenished with the Holy Ghost, looking upon him,
\v 10 said: O full of all guile, and all deceit, son of the devil, enemy of all justice, thou ceasest not to subvert the right ways of our Lord.
\v 11 And now behold the hand of our Lord upon thee, & thou shalt be blind, not seeing the sun until a time. And forthwith there fell dimness and darkness upon him, and going about he sought somebody that would give him his hand.
\v 12 Then the Proconsul, when he had seen that which was done, believed, marveling at the doctrine of our Lord.
\v 13 And when Paul and they that were with him had sailed from Paphos, they came to Perge in Pamphylia. And John departing from them, returned to Jerusalem.
\v 14 But they passing through Perge, came to Antioch in Pisidia: and entering into the Synagogue on the day of the Sabboth, they sat down.
\v 15 And after the lesson of the Law and the Prophets, the princes of the Synagogue sent to them, saying: Men brethren, if there be among you any sermon of exhortation to the people, speak.
\v 16 And Paul rising up, and with his hand beckoning for silence, said: Ye men of Israel, and you that fear God, harken.
\v 17 The God of the people of Israel chose our fathers, and exalted the people when they were sojourners in the land of Ægypt, and in a mighty arm brought them out thereof, \f + \fr 13:17 \ft Exod.\f*
\v 18 and for the space of forty years tolerated their manners in the desert. \f + \fr 13:18 \ft Iosue.\f*
\v 19 And destroying seven nations in the land of Chanaan, by lot he divided their land among them,
\v 20 as it were after four hundred and fifty years, and after these things he gave Judges, until Samuel the Prophet.
\v 21 And thenceforth they desired a king: & he gave them Saul the son of Cis, a man of the tribe of Benjamin, forty years. \x + \xo 13:21 \xt Iud. 1. Reg. 8.\x*
\v 22 and removing him, he raised them up David to be king: to whom giving testimony, he said: \add I have found David the son of Jesse, a man according to my heart, who shall do all my wills.\add* \x + \xo 13:22 \xt 1. Reg. 16.\x* \x + \xo 13:22 \xt Ps. 88, 21.\x*
\v 23 Of his seed God according to his promise hath brought forth to Israel a Saviour \sc Jesus\sc*, \x + \xo 13:23 \xt Psa. 131, 11.\x*
\v 24 John preaching before the face of his coming, baptism of penance to all the people of Israel. \x + \xo 13:24 \xt Lu. 3, 3.\x*
\v 25 And when John fulfilled his course, he said: Whom do you think me to be? I am not he: but behold there cometh after me, whose shoes of his feet I am not worthy to loose. \x + \xo 13:25 \xt Lu. 3, 15.\x*
\v 26 Men brethren, children of the stock of Abraham, & they among you that fear God; to you the word of this salvation was sent. \f + \fr 13:26 \ft The Epistle upon Tuesday in Easter week.\f*
\v 27 For they that inhabited Jerusalem, and the princes thereof, not knowing him, nor the voices of the prophets that are read every Sabboth, judging have fulfilled them,
\v 28 and finding no cause of death in him, desired of Pilate, that they might kill him. \x + \xo 13:28 \xt Lu. 23, 1.\x*
\v 29 And when they had consummated all things that were written of him, taking him down from the tree, they put him in a monument.
\v 30 But God raised him up from the dead the third day:
\v 31 who was seen for many days of them that came up together with him from Galilee into Jerusalem, who until this present are his witnesses to the people. \x + \xo 13:31 \xt Act. 1, 3.\x*
\v 32 And we preach unto you that promise which was made to our fathers:
\v 33 that God hath fulfilled this same <alt>to our children</alt>, raising up \sc Jesus\sc*, as in the second Psalm also it is written: \add My Son art thou, this day have I begotten thee.\add* \f + \fr 13:33 \ft to us their children,\f* \x + \xo 13:33 \xt Ps. 2, 7.\x*
\v 34 And that he raised him up from the dead, not to return now any more into corruption, thus he said: \add That I will give you the holy things of David faithful.\add* \x + \xo 13:34 \xt Esa. 55, 3.\x*
\v 35 And therefore in another place also he saith: \add Thou shalt not give thy holy one to see corruption.\add* \x + \xo 13:35 \xt Ps. 15, 10.\x*
\v 36 For David in his generation when he had served, according to the will of God slept: and he was laid to his fathers & saw corruption.
\v 37 But he whom God hath raised up, saw no corruption.
\v 38 Be it known therefore to you, men brethren, that through him, forgiveness of sins is preached to you, from all the things from the which you could not be justified by the law of Moyses.
\v 39 In him every one that believeth, is justified.
\v 40 Take heed therefore lest that come upon you which is spoken in the prophets,
\v 41 \add See ye contemners, and wonder, and perish: because I work a work in your days, a work which you will not believe, if any man shall tell it you.\add* \x + \xo 13:41 \xt Abac. 1, 5.\x*
\v 42 And they going forth, they desired them that the Sabboth following they would speak unto them these words. \f + \fr 13:42 \ft c the Gentiles desired\f*
\v 43 And when the Synagogue was dismissed, many of the Jews, and of the strangers serving God, followed Paul & Barnabas: who speaking exhorted them to continue in the grace of God. \f + \fr 13:43 \ft c devout proselytes,\f*
\v 44 But the next Sabboth the whole city almost assembled to hear the word of God.
\v 45 And the Jews seeing the multitudes, were replenished with envy, & contradicted those things which were said of Paul, blaspheming.
\v 46 Then Paul and Barnabas constantly said: To you it behoved us first to speak the word of God: but because you repel it, and judge yourselves unworthy of eternal life; behold we turn to the Gentiles. \f + \fr 13:46 \ft The Jews of their own free will repelling the truth, are unworthy of Christ and worthily forsaken: and the Gentiles though they believed specially by God's grace and preordination, yet they believe also by their own free will, which standeth well with God's providence.\f*
\v 47 For so our Lord commanded us: \add I have put thee to be the light of the Gentiles; that thou mayest be salvation unto the utmost of the earth.\add* \x + \xo 13:47 \xt Esa. 49, 6.\x*
\v 48 And the Gentiles hearing it, were glad, and glorified the word of our Lord: and there believed as many as were preordinate to life everlasting.
\v 49 And the word of our Lord was spread throughout the whole country.
\v 50 But the Jews stirred up religious and honest women, and the chief of the city, and raised persecution against Paul and Barnabas: and they did cast them forth out of their coasts.
\v 51 But they shaking off the dust of their feet against them, came to Iconium. \x + \xo 13:51 \xt Lu. 9, 5.\x*
\v 52 The Disciples also were replenished with joy and with the Holy Ghost.
\c 14
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass at Iconium that they entered together into the Synagogue of the Jews, and so spake, that a very great multitude of Jews and of the Greeks did believe.
\v 2 But the Jews that were incredulous, stirred up and incensed the hearts of the Gentiles to anger against the brethren.
\v 3 Along time therefore they abode, dealing confidently in our Lord, who gave testimony to the word of his grace, granting signs and wonders to be done by their hands.
\v 4 And the multitude of the city was divided: and certain of them indeed were with the Jews, but certain with the Apostles.
\v 5 And when the Gentiles and the Jews with their princes had made an assault, to use them contumeliously, and to stone them,
\v 6 understanding it, they fled to the cities of Lycaonia, Lystra and Derbe, and the whole country about, and there they were evangelizing.
\v 7 And a certain man at Lystra impotent of his feet sat there, lame from his mother's womb, that never had walked.
\v 8 This same heard Paul speaking. Who looking upon him, and seeing that he had faith for to be saved,
\v 9 he said with a loud voice: Stand up right on thy feet. And he leaped & walked.
\v 10 And the multitudes when they had seen what Paul had done, lifted up their voice in the Lycaonian tongue, saying: Gods made like to men, are descended to us.
\v 11 And they called Barnabas, Jupiter: but Paul Mercury, because he was the chief speaker.
\v 12 The Priest also of Jupiter that was before the city, bringing oxen and garlands before the gates, would with the people sacrifice. \f + \fr 14:12 \ft c διὸς τοῦ ὄντος\f*
\v 13 Which thing when the Apostles Barnabas and Paul heard, renting their coats, they leaped forth into the multitudes, crying
\v 14 and saying: Ye men, why do you these things? We also are mortal men like unto you, preaching to you for to convert from these vain things, to the living God that made the Heaven, and the earth, and the sea, and all things that are in them:
\v 15 who in the Generations past suffered all the Gentiles to go their own ways.
\v 16 Howbeit he left not himself without testimony, being beneficial from Heaven, giving rains, and fruitful seasons, filling our hearts with food and gladness. \f + \fr 14:16 \ft The Heathen might by the daily benefits of god have known him at the least to have been their Creator and only Lord, though the mystery of our Redemption were not opened to them.\f*
\v 17 And speaking these things, they scarce appeased the multitudes from sacrificing to them.
\v 18 But there came in certain Jews from Antioch and Iconium: and persuading the multitudes, and stoning Paul, they drew him out of the city, thinking him to be dead. \x + \xo 14:18 \xt 2. Cor. 11, 25.\x*
\v 19 But the Disciples compassing him round about, he rising up, entered into the city, and the next day he went forth with Barnabas unto Derbe.
\v 20 And when they had evangelized to that city, & had taught many, they returned to Lystra and Iconium, and to Antioch:
\v 21 confirming the hearts of the Disciples, and exhorting them to continue in the faith; and that by many tribulations we must enter into the Kingdom of God.
\v 22 And when they had ordained to them Priests in every Church, and had prayed with fastings, they commended them to our Lord in whom they believed. \f + \fr 14:22 \ft We see by this, first that SS. Paul & Barnabas were Bishops, having here authority to give Holy Orders: secondly, that there was even then a difference betwixt Bishops and Priests, though the name in the primitive Church was often used indifferently: lastly, that always fasting & praying were preparatives to the giving of Holy Orders.\f*
\v 23 And passing through Pisidia, they came into Pamphylia,
\v 24 and speaking the word of our Lord in Perge, they went down into Attalia:
\v 25 and from thence they sailed to Antioch, whence they had been delivered to the grace of God unto the work which they accomplished. \x + \xo 14:25 \xt Act, 13, 2.\x*
\v 26 And when they were come, and had assembled the Church, they reported what great things God had done with them, & that he had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles.
\v 27 And they abode no little time with the Disciples.
\c 15
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* certain coming down from Jewry, taught the brethren: That unless you be circumcised according to the manner of Moyses, you cannot be saved. \x + \xo 15:1 \xt Gal. 5, 2.\x*
\v 2 No little sedition therefore being risen to Paul and Barnabas against them, they appointed that Paul and Barnabas should go up, & certain others of <alt>the rest</alt>, to the Apostles and Priests unto Jerusalem, upon this question. \f + \fr 15:2 \ft them,\f* \f + \fr 15:2 \ft c ρεσβυτέρους.\f*
\v 3 They therefore being brought on their way by the Church, passed through Phoenice & Samaria, reporting the conversion of the Gentiles: and they made great joy to all the brethren.
\v 4 And when they were come to Jerusalem, they were received of the Church and of the Apostles and Ancients, declaring whatsoever God had done with them. \f + \fr 15:4 \ft c Ancients here, & often in this chapter, are the same that Priests vers. 2. as S. Hierom taketh it also 1. Pet. 5. &\f* \f + \fr 15:4 \ft c πρεσβυτέρων\f*
\v 5 And there arose certain of the heresy of the Pharisees that believed, saying, That they must be circumcised; commanded also to keep the law of Moyses.
\v 6 And the Apostles and Ancients assembled to consider of this word.
\v 7 And when there was made a great disputation, Peter rising up said to them: Men brethren, you know that of old days God among us chose, that by my mouth the Gentiles should hear the word of the Gospel, and believe. \f + \fr 15:7 \ft b See the Annot. vers. 28. toward the end.\f* \x + \xo 15:7 \xt Act. 10, 20.\x*
\v 8 And God which knoweth the hearts, gave testimony, giving unto them the Holy Ghost as well as to us, \x + \xo 15:8 \xt Act. 10, 45.\x*
\v 9 and hath put no difference between us and them, by faith purifying their hearts. \f + \fr 15:9 \ft By that faith which worketh by charity, for a dead faith cannot purify the heart of man. See chap. 16, 31.\f*
\v 10 Now therefore why tempt you God, to put a yoke upon the necks of the Disciples, which neither our fathers nor we have been able to bear?
\v 11 But by the grace of our Lord \sc Jesus Christ\sc* we believe to be saved, in like manner as they also.
\v 12 And all the multitude held their peace: and they heard Barnabas and Paul telling what great signs and wonders God had done among the Gentiles by them.
\v 13 And after they held their peace, James answered, saying: Men brethren, hear me.
\v 14 Simon hath told how God first visited to take of the Gentiles a people to his name.
\v 15 And to this accord the words of the Prophets, as it is written:
\v 16 \add After these things I will return, and will re-edify the tabernacle of David which was fallen, and the ruins thereof I will re-edify, and set it up:\add* \x + \xo 15:16 \xt Tim. 3, 5.\x*
\v 17 \add that the residue of men may seek after the Lord, and all nations upon whom my name is invocated, saith the Lord that doeth these things.\add*
\v 18 To our Lord was his own work known from the beginning of the world.
\v 19 For the which cause I judge, that they which of the Gentiles are converted to God, are not to be disquieted,
\v 20 but to write unto them that they refrain themselves from the contaminations of idols, and fornication, and strangled things, and blood.
\v 21 For Moyses of old times hath in every city them that preach him in the Synagogues, where he is read every Sabboth.
\v 22 Then it pleased the Apostles and Ancients with the whole Church, to choose men out of them, & to send to Antioch with Paul and Barnabas, Judas, who was surnamed Barsabas, & Silas, chief men among the Brethren,
\v 23 writing by their hands. The Apostles and Ancients, the brethren, to the brethren of the Gentiles that are at Antioch and in Syria and Cilicia, greeting. \f + \fr 15:23 \ft c Other Latin copies and the Greek read thus Writing by their hands an epistle containing these things.\f*
\v 24 Because we have heard that certain going forth from us have troubled you with words subverting your souls, to whom we gave no commandment:
\v 25 It hath pleased us being gathered in one, to choose out men & to send them unto you with our dearest Barnabas and Paul,
\v 26 men that have given their lives for the name of our Lord \sc Jesus Christ\sc*.
\v 27 We have sent therefore Judas and Silas who themselves also will in words report unto you the same things.
\v 28 For it hath seemed good to the Holy Ghost and to us, to lay no further burden upon you than these necessary things:
\v 29 That you abstain from the things immolated to idols, and blood, and that which is strangled, and fornication, from the which things keeping yourselves, you shall do well. Fare ye well.
\v 30 They therefore being dismissed went down to Antioch: and gathering the multitude, delivered the epistle.
\v 31 Which when they had read, they rejoiced upon the consolation:
\v 32 but Judas and Silas, themselves also being prophets, with many words comforted the brethren, and confirmed them.
\v 33 And having spent some time there, they were with peace dismissed of the brethren unto them that had sent them.
\v 34 But it seemed good unto Silas to remain there: and Judas departed alone:
\v 35 and Paul and Barnabas tarried at Antioch, teaching and evangelizing with many others the word of our Lord.
\v 36 And after certain days, Paul said to Barnabas, let us return and visit our brethren in all cities wherein we have preached the word of our Lord, how they do. \f + \fr 15:36 \ft Hereof our Catholic Bishops took up the necessary use of often visiting their flocks & cures committed to their charge, for confirmation in faith & virtue, & reformation of manners both of clergy & laity.\f* \x + \xo 15:36 \xt Act. 13, 14.\x*
\v 37 And Barnabas would have taken with them John also that was surnamed Mark.
\v 38 But Paul desired that he (as who had departed from them out of Pamphylia, & had not gone with them to the work) might not be received. \x + \xo 15:38 \xt Act. 13, 13.\x*
\v 39 And there rose a dissension, so that they departed one from another, & that, Barnabas indeed taking Mark sailed to Cypres.
\v 40 But Paul choosing Silas departed, being delivered of the brethren to the grace of God.
\v 41 And he walked through Syria and Cilicia, confirming the Churches: commanding them to keep the precepts of the Apostles & the Ancients. \f + \fr 15:41 \ft Not only the things commanded by Christ's express word, or written in the Scriptures (as our Heretics hold) but whatsoever the Apostles and Rulers of the Church command, is to be kept & obeyed. See these words repeated again c. 16, 4. & that in the Greek, lest any man cavil, because here the Greek hath them not.\f* \x + \xo 15:41 \xt Luc. 10, 11.\x*
\c 16
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* he came to Derbe and Lystra. And behold, there was a certain Disciple there named Timothee, the son of <alt>a widow</alt> woman that believed, of a father a Gentile. \f + \fr 16:1 \ft Jew\f*
\v 2 To this man the brethren that were in Lystra and Iconium, gave a good testimony.
\v 3 Him Paul would have to go forth with him: and taking him he circumcised him because of the Jews that were in those places. For they all knew that his father was a Gentile.
\v 4 And when they passed through the cities, they delivered unto them to keep the decrees that were decreed of the Apostles and Ancients which were at Jerusalem. \f + \fr 16:4 \ft Here again they take order that the decrees and articles of faith agreed upon in the Councel of Jerusalem, should be executed & observed, whereby we see both the great authority of Councels, & the diligence that all Prelates ought to have to see the decrees & Canons of the Councels put in execution.\f*
\v 5 And the Churches were confirmed in faith, and did abound in number daily.
\v 6 And passing through Phrygia and the country of Galatia, they were forbidden by the Holy Ghost to preach the word in Asia. \f + \fr 16:6 \ft This people had not the Gospel denied unto them altogether, but for a time: because (as Venerable Bede thinketh) God foresaw they would not believe, & so should have been more grievously damned.\f*
\v 7 And when they were come into Mysia, they attempted to go into Bithynia, and the Spirit of \sc Jesus\sc* permitted them not.
\v 8 And when they had passed through Mysia, they went down to Troas:
\v 9 and a vision by night was shewed to Paul. There was a certain man of Macedonia standing and beseeching him, and saying: Pass into Macedonia, and help us.
\v 10 And as soon as he had seen the vision, forthwith we sought to go into Macedonia, being assured that God had called us to evangelize to them.
\v 11 And sailing from Troas, we came with a straight course to Samothracia, and the day following to Neapolis:
\v 12 and from thence to Philippi, which is the first city of the part of Macedonia, a \add colonia.\add* And we were in this city certain days, abiding. \f + \fr 16:12 \ft Colonia, is such as city where the most inhabitants are strangers, sent thither from other great cities & States, namely from the Romans.\f*
\v 13 And upon the day of the Sabboths, we went forth without the gate beside a river, where it seemed that there was prayer: & sitting we spake to the women that were assembled.
\v 14 And a certain woman named Lydia, a seller of purple of the city of the Thyatirians, one that worshipped God, did hear: whose heart our Lord opened to attend to those things which were said of Paul.
\v 15 And when she was baptized, & her house, she besought us, saying: If you have judged me to be faithful to our Lord, enter into my house & tarry. And she constrained us.
\v 16 And it came to pass as we went to prayer, a certain wench having a Pythonical spirit, met us, that brought great gain to her masters by divining.
\v 17 This same following Paul & us, cried saying: These men are the servants of the high God, which preach unto you the way of salvation. \f + \fr 16:17 \ft Either the Devil was compelled by the virtue of Paul's presence to say truth, or else (as such do often times) he spake truth now, that they might the more trust him, and he better beguile them at other times.\f*
\v 18 And this she did many days. And Paul being sorry, and turning, said to the spirit: I command thee in the name of \sc Jesus Christ\sc* to go out from her. And he went out the same hour.
\v 19 But her masters seeing that the hope of their gain was gone, apprehending Paul and Silas, brought them into the market place to the Princes:
\v 20 and presenting them to the magistrates, they said: These men trouble our city, being Jews:
\v 21 and they preach a fashion which it is not lawful for us to receive, nor do, being Romans.
\v 22 And the people ran against them: and the magistrates tearing their coats, commanded them to be beaten with rods.
\v 23 And when they had laid many stripes upon them, they did cast them into prison, commanding the keeper that he should keep them diligently. \x + \xo 16:23 \xt 2. Cor. 11.\x*
\v 24 Who when he had received such commandment, cast them into the inner prison, and made their feet fast in the stocks.
\v 25 And at mid-night Paul and Silas praying, did praise God. And they that were in prison, heard them.
\v 26 But suddenly there was made a great earthquake, so that the foundations of the prison were shaken. And forthwith all the doors were opened: and the bands of all were loosed.
\v 27 And the keeper of the prison waked out of his sleep, and seeing the doors of the prison opened, drawing out his sword, would have killed himself, supposing that the prisoners had been fled.
\v 28 But Paul cried with a loud voice, saying: Do thyself no harm, for we are all here.
\v 29 And calling for light, he went in, and trembling fell down to Paul and Silas at their feet:
\v 30 and bringing them forth, he said: Masters, what must I do that I may be saved?
\v 31 But they said: Believe in our Lord \sc Jesus\sc*; and thou shalt be saved and thy house. \f + \fr 16:31 \ft It is no other faith that saveth but that which worketh by Charity. Aug. Enchirid. c. 67.\f*
\v 32 And they preached the word of our Lord to him with all that were in his house.
\v 33 And he taking them in the same hour of the night, washed their wounds: and himself was baptized and all his house incontinent. \f + \fr 16:33 \ft c Happy Jailers that do mercy toward their godly prisoners, and receive again by them such spiritual benefits.\f*
\v 34 And when he had brought them into his own house, he laid the table for them, and rejoiced with all his house, believing God.
\v 35 And when day was come, the magistrates sent the sergeants, saying: Let those men go.
\v 36 And the keeper of the prison told these words to Paul, That the magistrates have sent that you should be let go. Now therefore departing, go ye in peace.
\v 37 But Paul said to them: Being whipped openly, uncondemned, men that are Romans, they have cast us into prison: & now do they send us out secretly? Not so, but let them come, & let us out themselves.
\v 38 And the sergeants reported these words to the magistrates. And they were afraid hearing that they were Romans:
\v 39 and coming they besought them, & bringing them forth they desired them to depart out of the city.
\v 40 And going out of the prison, they entered in unto Lydia: and having seen the brethren, they comforted them, and departed.
\c 17
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* when they had walked through Amphipolis and Apollonia, they came to Thessalonica, where there was a Synagogue of the Jews.
\v 2 And Paul according to his custom entered in unto them, & three Sabboths he discoursed to them out of the Scriptures,
\v 3 declaring and insinuating that it behoved \sc Christ\sc* to suffer and to rise again from the dead: & that this is \sc Jesus Christ\sc*, whom I preach to you.
\v 4 And certain of them believed, and were joined to Paul and Silas, and of the Gentiles that served God a great multitude, and noble women not a few.
\v 5 But the Jews envying, & taking unto them of the rascal sort certain naughty men, and making a tumult, stirred the city: and besetting Jason's house, sought to bring them forth unto the people. \f + \fr 17:5 \ft Zelantes. This is the zeal of Heretics, and a lively pattern of their dealing at this day against Catholic Priests and preachers and the good Jasons that receive them.\f*
\v 6 And not finding them, they drew Jason and certain brethren to the princes of the city, crying, That these are they that stir up the world, and are come hither,
\v 7 whom Jason hath received, and all these do against the decrees of Cæsar, saying that there is another King, \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 8 And they moved the people, and the princes of the city hearing these things.
\v 9 And taking a satisfaction of Jason and of the rest, they dismissed them.
\v 10 But the brethren forthwith by night sent away Paul and Silas unto Beroea. Who when they were come, entered into the Synagogue of the Jews.
\v 11 (And these were more noble than they that are at Thessalonica, who received the word with all greediness, daily searching the scriptures, if these things were so.
\v 12 And many surely of them believed, and of honest women Gentiles, and men not a few.)
\v 13 And when the Jews in Thessalonica understood, that at Beroea also the word of God was preached by Paul, they came thither also, moving and troubling the multitude.
\v 14 And then immediately the brethren sent away Paul, to go unto the sea: but Silas and Timothee remained there.
\v 15 And they that conducted Paul, brought him as far as Athens, and receiving commandment of him to Silas and Timothee, that they should come to him very speedily, they departed.
\v 16 And when Paul expected them at Athens, his spirit was incensed within him, seeing the city given to idolatry.
\v 17 He disputed therefore in the Synagogue with the Jews, & them that served God, and in the market-place, every day with them that were there.
\v 18 And certain Philosophers of the Epicures and the Stoics disputed with him, and certain said, what is it that this word-sower would say? But others: He seemeth to be a preacher of new gods: because he preached to them \sc Jesus\sc* and the resurrection. \f + \fr 17:18 \ft b σπερμολόγος.\f* \f + \fr 17:18 \ft dæmoniorum.\f*
\v 19 And apprehending him, they led him to Areopagus, saying: May we know what this new doctrine is that thou speakest of?
\v 20 for thou bringest in certain new things to our ears. We will know therefore what these things may mean.
\v 21 (And all the Athenians, and the strangers sojourning there, employed themselves to nothing else but either to speak, or to hear some news.)
\v 22 But Paul standing in the midst of Areopagus, said: Ye men of Athens, in all things I perceive you as it were superstitious. \f + \fr 17:22 \ft The Epistle for S. Dionysius Areopagita. Octob. 9.\f*
\v 23 For passing by and seeing your idols, I found an altar also where upon was written: To the unknown God. That therefore which you worship, not knowing it, the same do I preach to you. \f + \fr 17:23 \ft c The Adversaries (in the new Test. 1580.) translate, your devotions, most corruptly against the nature of the Greek word (2. Thes. 2, 4.) and most wickedly, against the laudable devotion of good Christians, calling the Pagans idolatry and superstition, their devotions.\f* \f + \fr 17:23 \ft c τὰ σεβάσματα\f*
\v 24 The God that made the world and all things that are in it, he being Lord of Heaven & earth dwelleth not in temples made with hand, \f + \fr 17:24 \ft God is not concluded in Temples, nor needeth them for his necessity of dwelling, or other uses of indigence. See Annot. c. 7. Act. v. 48.\f* \x + \xo 17:24 \xt Act. 7, 48.\x*
\v 25 neither is he served with men's hands, needing any thing, whereas himself giveth life unto all, and breathing, and all things:
\v 26 and he made of one, all mankind, to inhabit upon the whole face of the earth, assigning set times, and the limits of their habitation,
\v 27 for to seek God, if happily they may feel or find him; although he be not far from every one of us:
\v 28 For in him we live and move and be, as certain also of your own poets said, \add For of his kind also we are.\add* \f + \fr 17:28 \ft Aratus.\f*
\v 29 Being therefore of God's kind, we may not suppose, the Divinity to be like unto gold or silver, or stone, the graving of art and device of man.
\v 30 And the times truly of this ignorance whereas God despised, now he denounceth unto men that all every-where do penance,
\v 31 for that he hath appointed a day wherein he will judge the world in equity, by a man whom he hath appointed, giving all men faith, raising him up from the dead.
\v 32 And when they had heard the resurrection of the dead, certain indeed mocked, but certain said: We will hear thee again concerning this point.
\v 33 So Paul went forth out of the midst of them.
\v 34 But certain men joining unto him, did believe: among whom was also Dionysius Areopagita, and a woman named Damaris, and others with them. \f + \fr 17:34 \ft Dionysius Areopagita.\f*
\c 18
\p
\v 1 \sc After\sc* these things, departing from Athens, he came to Corinth.
\v 2 and finding a certain Jew, named Aquila, born in Pontus, who of late was come out of Italy, & Priscilla his wife (because Claudius had commanded all Jews to depart from Rome,) he came to them.
\v 3 And because he was of the same craft, he remained with them, and wrought, (and they were tent-makers by their craft.)
\v 4 And he disputed in the synagogue every Sabboth, interposing the name of our Lord \sc Jesus\sc*, and he exhorted the Jews and the Greeks.
\v 5 And when Silas and Timothee were come from Macedonia, Paul was instant in preaching, testifying to the Jews that \sc Jesus\sc* is \sc Christ\sc*.
\v 6 But they contradicting and blaspheming, he shaking his garments, said to them: Your blood upon your own head: I being clean, from henceforth will go to the Gentiles.
\v 7 And departing thence, he entered into the house of a certain man, named Titus Justus, one that served God, whose house was adjoining to the synagogue.
\v 8 And Crispus the prince of the Synagogue believed our Lord, with all his house: & many of the Corinthians hearing believed, and were baptized.
\v 9 And our Lord said in the night by a vision to Paul: Do not fear, but speak, and hold not thy peace,
\v 10 for-because I am with thee: and no man shall set upon thee to hurt thee: for I have much people in this city.
\v 11 And he sat there a year & six months, teaching among them the word of God.
\v 12 But Gallio being Proconsul of Achaia, the Jews with one accord rose up against Paul, and brought him to the judgement seat,
\v 13 saying: That this man contrary to the Law persuadeth men to worship God.
\v 14 And Paul beginning to open his mouth, Gallio said to the Jews: If it were some unjust thing, or an heinous fact, O you men Jews, I should by reason bear you.
\v 15 But if they be questions of word and names, and of your law, yourselves look unto it: I will not be judge of these things.
\v 16 And he drove them from the judgement seat.
\v 17 And all apprehending Sosthenes the prince of the Synagogue, strook him before the judgement seat: and Gallio cared for none of those things.
\v 18 But Paul when he had stayed yet many days, taking his leave of the brethren, sailed to Syria, (and with him Priscilla and Aquila,) who had shorn his head in Cenchris. For he had a vow. \x + \xo 18:18 \xt Nu. 6, 18. Act. 21, 24.\x*
\v 19 And he came unto Ephesus, and them he left there. But himself entering into the Synagogue, disputed with the Jews.
\v 20 And when they desired him, that he would tarry a longer time, he consented not,
\v 21 but taking his leave, and saying: I will return to you again God willing, he departed from Ephesus.
\v 22 And going down to Cæsarea, he went up, and saluted the Church, and came down to Antioch.
\v 23 And having tarried there a certain time, he departed, walking in order through the country of Galatia and Phrygia, confirming all the Disciples.
\v 24 And a certain Jew, named Apollo, born at Alexandria, an eloquent man, came to Ephesus, mighty in the Scriptures. \f + \fr 18:24 \ft Apollo.\f*
\v 25 This man was taught the way of our Lord: and being fervent in spirit he spake, & taught diligently those things that pertain to \sc Jesus\sc*, knowing only the Baptism of John.
\v 26 This man therefore began to deal confidently in the Synagogue. Whom when Priscilla and Aquila had heard, they took him unto them, and expounded to him the way of our Lord more diligently.
\v 27 And whereas he was desirous to go to Achaia, the brethren exhorting wrote to the Disciples to receive him. Who, when he was come, profited them much that had believed.
\v 28 For he with vehemency convinced the Jews openly, shewing by the scriptures, that \sc Jesus\sc* is \sc Christ\sc*.
\c 19
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* it came to pass when Apollo was at Corinth, that Paul having gone through the higher parts came to Ephesus, and found certain Disciples: \f + \fr 19:1 \ft The Epistle upon Whitsun-eve.\f*
\v 2 and he said to them: Have you received the Holy Ghost, believing? But they said to him: Nay, neither have we heard whether there be a Holy Ghost.
\v 3 But he said: In what then were you baptized? Who said, In John's Baptism. \f + \fr 19:3 \ft c John's Baptism not sufficient.\f*
\v 4 And Paul said: John baptized the people with the Baptism of penance, saying, That they should believe in him that was to come after him, that is to say, in \sc Jesus\sc*. \f + \fr 19:4 \ft c Christ's Baptism necessary.\f* \x + \xo 19:4 \xt Mt. 3, 11. Mr. 1, 8. Lu. 3, 16.\x*
\v 5 Hearing these things, they were baptized in the name of our Lord \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 6 And when Paul had imposed hands on them, the Holy Ghost came upon them, & they spake with tongues, and prophesied. \f + \fr 19:6 \ft S. Paul ministered the Sacrament of Confirmation. See annot. c. 8, 17.\f*
\v 7 And all the men were about twelve.
\v 8 And entering into the Synagogue, he spake confidently for three months, disputing & exhorting of the Kingdom of God.
\v 9 But when certain were indurate, and believed not, ill-speaking the way of our Lord before the multitude, departing from them, he separated the Disciples, daily disputing in the school of one Tyrannus.
\v 10 And this was done for the space of two years, so that all which dwelt in Asia, heard the word of our Lord, Jews and Gentiles.
\v 11 And God wrought by the hand of Paul miracles not common:
\v 12 so that there were also brought from his body napkins or handkerchiefs upon the sick, and the diseases departed from them, and the wicked spirits went out.
\v 13 And certain also of the Judaical exorcists that went about, assayed to invocate upon them that had evil spirits, the name of our Lord \sc Jesus\sc*, saying: I adjure you by \sc Jesus\sc* whom Paul preacheth.
\v 14 And there were certain sons of Sceva a Jew, chief Priest, seven, that did this.
\v 15 But the wicked spirit answering, said to them: \sc Jesus\sc* I know, and Paul I know: but you, what are ye?
\v 16 And the man in whom the wicked spirit was, leaping upon them, and mastering <alt>both</alt>, prevailed against them, so that they fled out of that house naked and wounded. \f + \fr 19:16 \ft them\f*
\v 17 And this was made notorious to all the Jews and the Gentiles that dwelt at Ephesus: and fear fell upon all them, and the name of our Lord \sc Jesus\sc* was magnified.
\v 18 And many of them that believed, came confessing & declaring their deeds. \f + \fr 19:18 \ft They made not only a general confession wherein all men shew themselves alike to be sinners, as our Protestants do: but every one confessed his own proper deeds and faults.\f*
\v 19 And many of them that had followed curious things, brought together their books, and burnt them before all: and counting the prices of them, they found the money to be fifty thousand pence.
\v 20 So mightily increased the word of God and was confirmed. \f + \fr 19:20 \ft The 6. part.\f*
\v 21 And when these things were ended, Paul purposed in the Spirit, when he had passed through Macedonia and Achaia, to go to Jerusalem, saying: After I shall have been there, I must see Rome also. \f + \fr 19:21 \ft Of taking away the Gospel from Hierusalem the head city of the Jews, and giving it to ROME the head city of the Gentiles.\f*
\v 22 And sending into Macedonia two of them that ministered unto him, Timothee and Erastus, himself remained for a time in Asia.
\v 23 And at that time there was made no little trouble about the way of our Lord.
\v 24 For one named Demetrius, a silver-smith, that made silver temples of Diana, procured to the artificers no small gain: \f + \fr 19:24 \ft c The Protestants translate, shrines, in the Bible an. 1577: to make the people think that it toucheth the holy shrines of Saints: most corruptly, the Greek signifying plainly, temples, and that of heathen gods.\f* \f + \fr 19:24 \ft c ναοὺς.\f*
\v 25 whom calling together and them that were the same kind of workmen, he said: Sirs, you know that our gain is of this occupation;
\v 26 and you see, and hear that this same Paul by persuasion hath averted a great multitude not only of Ephesus, but almost of all Asia, saying: That they are not gods which be made by hands.
\v 27 And not only unto us is this part in danger to be reproved, but also the temple of great Diana shall be reputed for nothing, yea & her majesty shall begin to be destroyed, whom all Asia & the world worshippeth.
\v 28 Hearing these things they were replenished with anger, and cried out saying: Great is Diana of the Ephesians.
\v 29 And the whole city was filled with confusion, and they ran violently with one accord into the theater, catching Gaius & Aristarchus Macedonians, Paul's companions.
\v 30 And when Paul would have entered in to the people, the Disciples did not permit him.
\v 31 And certain also of the Princes of Asia that were his friends, sent unto him, desiring that he would not adventure himself into the theater:
\v 32 and others cried another thing. For the assembly was confuse, & the more part knew not for what cause they were assembled.
\v 33 And of the multitude they drew forth Alexander, the Jews thrusting him forward. But Alexander with his hand desiring silence, would have given the people satisfaction.
\v 34 Whom as soon as they perceived to be a Jew, there was made one voice of all, almost for the space of two hours crying out: Great is Diana of the Ephesians.
\v 35 And when the Scribe had appeased the multitudes, he saith: Ye men of Ephesus, for what man is there that knoweth not the city of the Ephesians to be a worshipper of great Diana, and Jupiter's child? \f + \fr 19:35 \ft c Here the Heretics add to the text this word, image, more than is in the Greek, to put a scruple into the people's mind concerning holy images.\f* \f + \fr 19:35 \ft c τοῦ διοπετοῦς.\f*
\v 36 Forasmuch therefore as these things cannot be gainsaid, you must be quieted, and do nothing rashly.
\v 37 For you have brought these men, being neither sacrilegious, nor blaspheming your goddess.
\v 38 But if Demetrius & the artificers that are with him, have matter to say against any man, there are Courts kept in the common place, & there are Proconsuls; let them accuse one another.
\v 39 And if you ask any other matter, it may be resolved in a lawful assembly.
\v 40 For we are in danger also to be accused for this day's sedition: whereas there is no man guilty by whom we may give an account of this concourse. And when he had said these things, he dismissed the assembly.
\c 20
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* after that the tumult was ceased, Paul calling the Disciples, and exhorting them, took his leave, and set forward to go into Macedonia.
\v 2 And when he had walked through those parts, & had exhorted them with much speech, he came to Greece:
\v 3 where when he had spent three months, the Jews laid wait for him as he was about to sail into Syria: and he had counsel to return through Macedonia.
\v 4 And there accompanied him Sosipater of Pyrrhus, of Beroea: and of Thessalonians, Aristarchus, and Secundus: and Caius of Derbe, and Timothee: and of Asia, Tychicus and Trophimus.
\v 5 These going before, stayed for us at Troas:
\v 6 But we sailed after the days of Azymes from Philippi, and came to them unto Troas in five days, where we abode seven days.
\v 7 And in the first of the Sabboth when we were assembled to break bread, Paul disputed with them, being to depart on the morrow: and he continued the sermon until mid-night. \f + \fr 20:7 \ft S. Paul did here break bread on the Sunday as it is broken in the Sacrament of the body of Christ, and had both before & after the celebrating of the Sacrament a sermon to the people. Aug. ep. 86. ad Casulanum. Vener. Beda in 20. Act.\f*
\v 8 And there were a great number of lamps in the upper chamber where we were assembled.
\v 9 And a certain young man named Eutychus, sitting upon the window, whereas he was oppressed with heavy sleep: (Paul disputing long) driven by sleep, fell from the third loft down, and was taken up dead.
\v 10 To whom when Paul was gone down, he lay upon him: and embracing him he said: Be not troubled, for his soul is in him.
\v 11 And going up and breaking bread and tasting, and having talked sufficiently to them until day light, so he departed.
\v 12 And they brought the lad alive, & were not a little comforted.
\v 13 But we going up into the ship, sailed to Asson, from thence meaning to receive Paul; for so he had ordained, himself purposing to journey by land.
\v 14 And when he had found us in Asson, taking him with us we came to Mitylene.
\v 15 And sailing thence, the day following we came over against Chios: and the other day we arrived at Samos: and the day following we came to Miletum.
\v 16 For Paul had purposed to sail leaving Ephesus, lest any stay should be made him in Asia. For he hastened, if it were possible for him, to keep the day of Pentecost at Jerusalem.
\v 17 And sending from Miletum to Ephesus, he called the Ancients of the Church. \f + \fr 20:17 \ft The Epistle for S. Steven Pope. Aug. 2.\f* \f + \fr 20:17 \ft c That is, Priests as Act. 15, 4. See the marginal annot. there.\f* \f + \fr 20:17 \ft c πρεσβυτέρους\f*
\v 18 Who being come to him, and assembled together, he said to them: You know from the first day that I entered into Asia, in what manner I have been with you all the time, \x + \xo 20:18 \xt Act. 19, 1.\x*
\v 19 serving our Lord with all humility and tears, and tentations that did chance to me by the conspiracies of the Jews:
\v 20 How I have withdrawn nothing that was profitable, but that I preached it to you, and taught you openly and from house to house,
\v 21 testifying to Jews and Gentiles penance toward God, and faith in our Lord \sc Jesus Christ\sc*. \f + \fr 20:21 \ft Apostolic preaching commendeth not faith only but penance also to the people.\f*
\v 22 And now behold, being bound by the spirit, I go to Jerusalem; not knowing what things shall befall me in it,
\v 23 but that the Holy Ghost throughout all cities doth protest to me, saying: that bands and tribulations abide me at Jerusalem.
\v 24 But I fear none of these things, neither do I make my life more precious than myself, so that I may consummate my course & ministry which I received of our Lord \sc Jesus\sc*, to testify the Gospel of the grace of God.
\v 25 And now behold I do know, that you shall no more see my face all you, through whom I have passed preaching the Kingdom of God.
\v 26 Wherefore I take you to witness this present day that I am clear from the blood of all.
\v 27 For I have not spared to declare unto you all the counsel of God.
\v 28 Take heed to yourselves and to the whole flock wherein the Holy Ghost hath placed you bishops, to rule the Church of God which he hath purchased with his own blood. \f + \fr 20:28 \ft Bishops or Priests (for then these names were sometime used indifferently) governors of the Church of God, & placed in that room & high function by the Holy Ghost.\f*
\v 29 I know that after my departure there will ravening wolves enter in among you, not sparing the flock.
\v 30 And out of your own selves shall arise men speaking perverse things, to draw away Disciples after themselves.
\v 31 For the which cause be vigilant, keeping in memory that for three years night & day I ceased not with tears to admonish every one of you.
\v 32 And now I commend you to God and to the word of his grace, who is able to edify, and to give inheritance in all the sanctified.
\v 33 No man's silver and gold or garment have I coveted.
\v 34 Yourselves know that for such things as were needful for me and them that are with me, these hands have ministered.
\v 35 I have shewed you all things, that so labouring, you must receive the weak, and remember the word of our Lord \sc Jesus\sc*, because he said: It is a more blessed thing to give rather than to take.
\v 36 And when he had said these things, falling on his knees he prayed with all them.
\v 37 And there was great weeping made of all; and falling upon the neck of Paul, they kissed him,
\v 38 being sorry most of all for the word which he had said, that they should see his face no more. And they brought him going unto the ship.
\c 21
\p
\v 0 keep Moyses' Law: 27. he is invaded by the infidel Jews, \add and ready to be murdered by them, until the Roman soldiers do rescue him.\add*
\v 1 \sc And\sc* when it came to pass that we sailed, being carried from them, with a straight course we came to Coos, and the day following to Rhodes, and from thence to Patara.
\v 2 And when we had found a ship that passed over to Phoenice, going up into it we sailed.
\v 3 And when we were in the sight of Cypres, leaving it on the left hand, we sailed into Syria, and came to Tyre: for there the ship was to discharge her load.
\v 4 And finding Disciples, we tarried there seven days: who said to Paul by the Spirit, that he should not go up to Jerusalem.
\v 5 And the days being expired, departing we went forward, all bringing us on the way, with their wives and children, till we were out of the city: and falling upon our knees on the shore, we prayed.
\v 6 And when we had bid one another farewell, we went up into the ship; and they returned unto their own.
\v 7 But we having ended the navigation, from Tyre came down to Ptolomais: and saluting the brethren, we tarried one day with them.
\v 8 And the next day departing, we came to Cæsarea. And entering into the house of Philip the Evangelist, who was one of the seven, we tarried with him. \x + \xo 21:8 \xt Act. 6, 5.\x*
\v 9 And he had four daughters virgins, that did prophesy. \f + \fr 21:9 \ft As S. Peter had a wife, but used her not after his calling, as it is noted elsewhere out of S. Hierom Luc. 4, 38: so may it be said of S. Philip being Deacon.\f*
\v 10 And as we abode there for certain days, there came a certain Prophet from Jewry, named Agabus.
\v 11 He, when he was come to us, took Paul's girdle: and binding his own feet & hands, he said: Thus saith the Holy Ghost: The man whose girdle this is, so shall the Jews bind in Jerusalem, and shall deliver him into the hands of the Gentiles.
\v 12 Which when we had heard, we and they that were of the same place, desired him that he would not go up to Jerusalem.
\v 13 Then Paul answered, and said: What do you, weeping and afflicting my heart? for I am ready not only to be bound, but to die also in Jerusalem for the name of our Lord \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 14 And when we could not persuade him, we ceased, saying: The will of our Lord be done.
\v 15 And after these days, being prepared, we went up to Jerusalem.
\v 16 And there came also of the Disciples from Cæsarea with us, bringing with them one Jason a Cyprian (with whom we should lodge) an old Disciple.
\v 17 And when we were come to Jerusalem, the brethren received us gladly.
\v 18 And the day following Paul went in with us to James, and all the Ancients were assembled.
\v 19 Whom when he had saluted, he told particularly what God had done among the Gentiles by his ministry.
\v 20 But they hearing it, magnified God, and said to him: Thou seest (brother) how many thousands there are among the Jews that have believed: and all are zelatours of the Law.
\v 21 But they have heard of thee that thou doest teach those Jews that are among the Gentiles, to depart from Moyses: saying that they ought not to circumcise their children, nor walk according to the custom.
\v 22 What is it then? needs must the multitude assemble: for they will hear that thou art come.
\v 23 Do this therefore which we tell thee. There are with us four men, that have a vow on them.
\v 24 Taking these unto thee, sanctify thyself with them; and bestow on them, that they may shave their heads: and all shall know that the things which they heard of thee, are false: but that thyself also walkest keeping the Law. \x + \xo 21:24 \xt Nu. 6, 18.\x*
\v 25 But concerning them that believe of the Gentiles, we have written, decreeing that they should refrain themselves from the immolated to idols, and blood, and suffocated, and fornication. \x + \xo 21:25 \xt Act. 15, 20.\x*
\v 26 Then Paul taking the men unto him, the next day being purified with them entered into the temple, shewing the accomplishment of the days of the purification, until an oblation was offered for every one of them. \x + \xo 21:26 \xt Nu. 6, 13.\x*
\v 27 But whiles the seven days were a finishing, those Jews that were of Asia, when they had seen him in the temple, stirred up all the people, and laid hands upon him,
\v 28 crying: Ye men of Israel, help: this is the man that against the people and the Law and this place teaching all men every-where, hath also moreover brought in Gentiles into the temple, and hath violated this holy place.
\v 29 (For they had seen Trophimus the Ephesian in the city with him, whom they supposed that Paul had brought into the temple.)
\v 30 And the whole city was in an uproar: and there was made a concourse of the people. And apprehending Paul, they drew him forth of the temple: and immediately the doors were shut.
\v 31 And as they sought to kill him, it was told the Tribune of the band, That all Jerusalem is in a confusion.
\v 32 Who forthwith taking unto him soldiers and Centurions, ran down to them. Who, when they had seen the Tribune and the soldiers, ceased to strike Paul.
\v 33 Then the Tribune coming near apprehended him, and commanded him to be bound with two chains: and he demanded who he was, and what he had done.
\v 34 And some cried one thing, some another, in the multitude. And whereas he could not know the certainty for the tumult, he commanded him to be led into the castle. \f + \fr 21:34 \ft c In castra. So in the places following.\f*
\v 35 And when he was come to the stairs, it chanced that he was carried of the soldiers because of the violence of the people.
\v 36 For the multitude of the people followed, crying: Away with him.
\v 37 And when Paul began to be brought into the castle, he saith to the Tribune: is it lawful for me to speak something to thee? Who said: Canst thou speak Greek?
\v 38 Art not thou the Ægyptian that before these days did raise a tumult, and didst lead forth into the desert four thousand men that were murderers?
\v 39 And Paul said to him: I am a man truly a Jew of Tarsus, a citizen not of an obscure city of Cilicia. And I desire thee, permit me to speak to the people. \x + \xo 21:39 \xt Act. 22, 3.\x*
\v 40 And when he had permitted him, Paul standing on the stairs, beckoned with his hand to the people. And great silence being made, he spake unto them in the Hebrew tongue, saying.
\c 22
\p
\v 1 \sc Men\sc* brethren and fathers, hear what account I do render now unto you.
\v 2 (And when they had heard that he spake to them in the Hebrew tongue, they did the more keep silence.
\v 3 And he saith:) I am a man a Jew, born at Tarsus in Cilicia, but brought up in this city, at the feet of Gamaliel instructed according to the verity of the law of the fathers, an emulator of the Law as also all you are this day: \x + \xo 22:3 \xt Act. 21, 39.\x*
\v 4 who persecuted this way unto death, binding & delivering into custodies men & women, \x + \xo 22:4 \xt Act. 8, 3.\x*
\v 5 as the high Priest doth give me testimony, and all the Ancients. Of whom receiving letters also to the brethren, I went to Damascus, that I might bring them thence bound to Jerusalem, to be punished. \x + \xo 22:5 \xt Act. 9, 2.\x*
\v 6 And it came to pass as I was going, and drawing nigh to Damascus at mid-day, suddenly from Heaven there shone round about me much light:
\v 7 and falling on the ground, I heard a voice saying to me: Saul, Saul, why persecutest thou me?
\v 8 And I answered: Who are thou Lord? And he said to me: I am \sc Jesus\sc* of Nazareth, whom thou persecutest.
\v 9 And they that were with me, saw the light indeed, but the voice they heard not of him that spake with me.
\v 10 And I said: What shall I do Lord? And our Lord said to me: Arise and go to Damascus; and there it shall be told thee of all things that thou must do.
\v 11 And whereas I did not see for the brightness of that light, being led of my companions by the hand, I came to Damascus.
\v 12 And one Ananias, a man according to the Law, having testimony of all the Jews' inhabitants,
\v 13 coming to me, and standing by me, said to me: Brother Saul, look up. And I the self-same hour looked upon him.
\v 14 But he said: The God of our fathers hath preordained thee, that thou shouldest know his will, and see the just one, and hear a voice from his mouth:
\v 15 because thou shalt be his witness to all men, of those things which thou hast seen and heard.
\v 16 And now what tarriest thou? Rise up, and be baptized, and wash away thy sins invocating his name. \f + \fr 22:16 \ft The Sacrament of Baptism doth itself wash away sins as here is plain, & therefore doth not only signify (as the Heretics affirm) that our sins be forgiven before, or otherwise by faith only remitted. Whereby the Church's doctrine is proved to be fully agreeable to the Scriptures, that the Sacraments give grace ex opere operato, that is, by the force & virtue of the work and word, done & said in the Sacrament.\f*
\v 17 And it befell me returning into Jerusalem, and praying in the temple, that I was in a trance,
\v 18 and saw him saying unto me: Make haste, and depart quickly out of Jerusalem: because they will not receive thy testimony of me.
\v 19 And I said, Lord, they know that I did cast into prison and beat in every Synagogue them that believed in thee.
\v 20 And when the blood of Steven thy witness was shed, I stood by and consented, and kept the garments of them that killed him. \f + \fr 22:20 \ft c μάρτυρος. Act. 7, 38.\f* \f + \fr 22:20 \ft Not only the Principals, but all that consent to the death or vexation of Christian men for the Catholic faith, do highly offend: which the Apostle confesseth here, that God's mercy may be more notoriously glorified in him hereby.\f*
\v 21 And he said to me: Go, for into the Gentiles a far will I send thee.
\v 22 And they heard him until this word, and they lifted up their voice, saying: Away with such an one from the earth: for it is not meet he should live.
\v 23 And when they cried out, and threw off their garments, and cast dust into the air,
\v 24 the Tribune commanded him to be carried into the castle, and to be beaten with whips, & that he should be tormented: to know for what cause they did so cry at him.
\v 25 And when they had bound him very straight with thongs, Paul saith to the Centurion standing by him: Is it lawful for you to whip a man that is a Roman and uncondemned?
\v 26 Which the Centurion hearing, went to the Tribune, and told him, saying: What wilt thou do? for this man is a citizen of Rome.
\v 27 And the Tribune coming, said to him: Tell me, art thou a Roman? But he said: Yea.
\v 28 And the Tribune answered: I obtained this city with a great sum. And Paul said: But I was also born to it.
\v 29 Immediately therefore they departed from him that were to torment him. The Tribune also feared after he understood that he was a citizen of Rome, and because he had bound him.
\v 30 But the next day meaning to know more diligently for what cause he was accused of the Jews, he loosed him, and commanded the Priests to come together and all the Council: & bringing forth Paul, he set him among them. \f + \fr 22:30 \ft c ἀρχιερεῖς.\f*
\c 23
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* Paul looking upon the Council, said: Men brethren, I with all good conscience have conversed before God, until this present day.
\v 2 And the high Priest Ananias commanded them that stood by him, to smite him on the mouth.
\v 3 Then Paul said to him: God shall strike thee, thou whited wall. And thou sitting judgest me according to the law, and contrary to law doest thou command me to be smitten? \f + \fr 23:3 \ft He said not this through perturbation of mind or of a passion, but by way of prophecy, that this figurative high priesthood then trimmed like a whited wall, was to be destroyed, whereas now the true priesthood of Christ was come. Beda in hunc lo.\f*
\v 4 And they that stood by, said: Doest thou revile the high Priest of God?
\v 5 And Paul said: I knew not, brethren, that he is the high Priest. For it is written: \add The prince of thy people thou shalt not misspeak.\add* \x + \xo 23:5 \xt Exo. 22, 28.\x*
\v 6 And Paul knowing that the one part was of Sadducees, and the other of Pharisees, he cried out in the Council: Men brethren, I am a Pharisee, the son of Pharisees: of the hope and resurrection of the dead am I judged. \f + \fr 23:6 \ft Such prudent evasions from danger are lawful. Which S. Chrysostom calleth (specially in this Apostle) the wisdom of the serpent, as otherwise in his teaching and preaching & patience he used the simplicity of a dove.\f* \x + \xo 23:6 \xt Phil. 3, 5.\x*
\v 7 And when he had said these things, there rose dissension between the Pharisees and Sadducees; and the multitude was divided.
\v 8 For the Sadducees say there is no resurrection, nor Angel, nor spirit: but the Pharisees confess both. \x + \xo 23:8 \xt Mt. 22, 23.\x*
\v 9 And there was made a great cry. And certain of the Pharisees rising up, strove saying: We find no evil in this man. What if a spirit hath spoken to him, or an Angel?
\v 10 And when there was risen great dissension, the Tribune fearing lest Paul should be torn in pieces by them, commanded the soldiers to go down, and to take him out of the midst of them, and to bring him into the castle.
\v 11 And the night following our Lord standing by him, said: Be constant; for as thou hast testified of me in Jerusalem, so must thou testify at Rome also. \f + \fr 23:11 \ft Though God who could not lie, had promised Paul that he should go to Rome; yet the Apostle omitted not human means to defend himself from his enemies and otherwise. Neither said he as the Heretics called Predestinates, Let them do what they will, they cannot hurt me, for I am predestinate to go to Rome. See his doings and sayings to save himself, in the chap. following.\f*
\v 12 And when day was come, certain of the Jews gathered themselves together, & vowed themselves, saying: that they would neither eat nor drink till they killed Paul.
\v 13 And they were more than forty men that had made this conspiracy:
\v 14 who came to the chief priests and the ancients, and said: By execration we have vowed ourselves, that we will eat nothing, till we kill Paul.
\v 15 Now therefore give you knowledge to the Tribune with the Council, that he bring him forth to you, as if you meant to know some more certainty touching him. But we, before he come near, are ready for to kill him.
\v 16 Which when Paul's sister's son had heard, of their lying in wait, he came and entered into the castle and told Paul.
\v 17 And Paul calling to him one of the Centurions, said: Bring this young man to the Tribune, for he hath something to tell him.
\v 18 And he taking him, brought him to the Tribune, and said: The prisoner Paul desired me to bring this young man unto thee, having something to say to thee. \f + \fr 23:18 \ft c See the courtesy & equity of Heathen Officers toward their prisoners, to save them from all injury and villainy.\f*
\v 19 And the Tribune taking him by the hand, went aside with him apart, and asked him: What is it that thou hast to tell me?
\v 20 And he said: The Jews have agreed to desire thee, that tomorrow thou wilt bring forth Paul into the Council, as though they meant to inquire some more certainty touching him.
\v 21 But do not thou credit them; for there lie in wait for him more than forty men of them, which have vowed neither to eat nor to drink, till they kill him: and they are now ready, expecting thy promise.
\v 22 The Tribune therefore dismissed the young man, commanding that he should speak to no man that he had notified these things unto him.
\v 23 And calling two Centurions, he said to them: Make ready two hundred soldiers, to go as far as Cæsarea, and seventy horsemen, and lances two hundred, from the third hour of the night:
\v 24 and prepare beasts: that setting Paul on, they might bring him safe to Felix the President.
\v 25 (For he feared lest perhaps the Jews might take him away, and kill him, and himself afterward should sustain reproach, as though he would have taken money)
\v 26 writing a letter containing this much: \add Claudius Lysias to the most excellent President Felix, greeting.\add*
\v 27 This man being apprehended of the Jews, and ready to be killed of them, I coming in with the band delivered him, understanding that he is a Roman:
\v 28 and meaning to know the cause that they objected unto him, I brought him down into their Council.
\v 29 Whom I found to be accused concerning questions of their law: but having no crime worthy of death or of bands.
\v 30 And when it was told me of ambushments that they had prepared against him, I sent him to thee, signifying also to the accusers, to speak before thee. Fare-well.
\v 31 And the soldiers according as it was commanded them, taking Paul, brought him by night to Antipatris.
\v 32 And the next day sending away the horse-men to go with him, they returned to the castle.
\v 33 Who when they were come to Cæsarea, and had delivered the letter to the President, they did set Paul also before him.
\v 34 And when he had read, and had asked of what province he was: and understanding that of Cilicia:
\v 35 I will hear thee, said he, when thy accusers are come. And he commanded him to be kept in Herod's palace.
\c 24
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* after five days the high priest Ananias descended, with certain ancients and one Tertullus an orator, who went to the President against Paul.
\v 2 And Paul being cited, Tertullus began to accuse, saying: Whereas we live in much peace by thee, & many things are corrected by thy providence,
\v 3 we do always & in all places receive it, most excellent Felix, with all thanks-giving.
\v 4 But lest I hinder thee any longer, I desire thee of thy clemency briefly to hear us.
\v 5 We have found this man pestiferous, & raising seditions to all the Jews in the whole world, and author of the sedition of the sect of the Nazarenes. \f + \fr 24:5 \ft c τῆς αἱρέσεως.\f*
\v 6 Who also hath attempted to violate the temple, whom also being apprehended we would have judged according to our law.
\v 7 But Lysias the Tribune coming in, with great force took him away out of our hands,
\v 8 commanding his accusers to come to thee, of whom thou mayest thyself judging, understand of all these things, whereof we accuse him.
\v 9 And the Jews also added, saying that these things were so.
\v 10 But Paul answered: (the President making a sign unto him for to speak) Knowing that of many years thou art judge over this nation, I will with good courage answer for myself.
\v 11 For thou mayest understand that it is not above twelve days to me, since I went up to adore in Jerusalem.
\v 12 And neither in the temple did they find me disputing with any man, or causing concourse of the multitude, neither in the synagogues, nor in the city:
\v 13 neither can they prove unto thee the things whereof they now accuse me.
\v 14 But this I confess to thee, that according to the sect, which they call heresy, I do so serve <alt>the Father my God</alt>, believing all things that are written in the Law & the Prophets: \f + \fr 24:14 \ft c κατὰ τὴν ὁδὸν\f* \f + \fr 24:14 \ft Because Tertullus the Jews' orator called Christian religion the sect or (as it is there vers. 5. in the Greek) the heresy of the Nazarens: S. Paul answereth and sheweth that it is no heresy. And as for the word, Sect, in this place: it is in the Greek, According to the way, which they call heresy, as also Act. 9, 2. 24, 22. And therefore the word sect here is so taken. See Annot. c. 28, 22.\f* \f + \fr 24:14 \ft the God of my Fathers, (or) the Father, and my God,\f*
\v 15 having hope in God, the which these also themselves expect, that there shall be a resurrection of just and unjust.
\v 16 In this myself also do study to have a conscience without offence toward God and toward men always.
\v 17 And after many years I came to bestow alms upon my nation, & oblations, and vows. \x + \xo 24:17 \xt Ro. 15, 28.\x*
\v 18 In the which they found me purified in the temple: not with multitude nor with tumult. \x + \xo 24:18 \xt Act. 21, 26.\x*
\v 19 But certain Jews of Asia, who ought to be present before thee and to accuse, if they had any thing against me:
\v 20 or let these men themselves say, if they have found in me any iniquity, forasmuch as I stand in the Council,
\v 21 but of this one voice only that I cried standing among them, That of the resurrection of the dead am I judged this day of you. \x + \xo 24:21 \xt Act. 23, 6.\x*
\v 22 And Felix deferred them, knowing most certainly of this way, saying: When Lysias the Tribune is come down, I will hear you.
\v 23 And he commanded the Centurion to keep him, and that he should have rest, neither to prohibit any of his to minister unto him.
\v 24 And after some days, Felix coming with Drusilla his wife, which was a Jew, called Paul, and heard of him the faith that is in Christ \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 25 And he disputing of justice and chastity, and of the judgement to come, Felix being terrified, answered: For this time, go thy way: but in time convenient I will send for thee. \f + \fr 24:25 \ft The Apostolic teaching was not of only or special faith, but of justice, & chastity, & judgement, that is to say, of the terror of Hell and other God's judgments in the next life answerable to our deeds in this world: by which the hearers were first terrified, and so induced to penance. How say Heretics then that such things make men hypocrites?\f*
\v 26 hoping also withal, that money would be given him of Paul; for the which cause also oftentimes sending for him, he spake with him.
\v 27 But when two years were ended, Felix had a Successor Portius Festus. And Felix being willing to shew the Jews a pleasure, left Paul in prison.
\c 25
\p
\v 1 \sc Festus\sc* therefore when he was come into the province, after three days went up to Jerusalem from Cæsarea.
\v 2 And the chief Priests, and principal men of the Jews went unto him against Paul: and they desired him,
\v 3 requesting favour against him, that he would command him to be brought to Jerusalem, laying wait for to kill him in the way.
\v 4 But Festus answered, that Paul is kept in Cæsarea: and that he would very shortly go thither.
\v 5 They therefore, saith he, that are of ability among you, going down with me, if there be any crime in the man, let them accuse him.
\v 6 And having tarried among them not above eight or ten days, he went down to Cæsarea, and the next day he sat in the judgement seat: and he commanded Paul to be brought.
\v 7 Who being brought, there stood about him the Jews that were come down from Jerusalem, objecting many and grievous causes which they could not prove; \f + \fr 25:7 \ft c crimes as v. 27.\f*
\v 8 Paul making answer, That neither against the law of the Jews, nor against the temple, nor against Cæsar have I any thing offended.
\v 9 But Festus willing to shew the Jews a pleasure, answering Paul, said: Wilt thou go up to Jerusalem, and there be judged of these things before me?
\v 10 And Paul said: At Cæsar's judgement seat do I stand, where I ought to be judged: the Jews I have not hurt, as thou very well knowest.
\v 11 For if I have hurt them, or done any thing worthy of death, I refuse not to die. But if none of those things be, whereof these accuse me, no man can give me to them. I appeal to Cæsar. \f + \fr 25:11 \ft If S. Paul both to save himself from whipping and from death sought by the Jews, doubted not to cry for succour of the Roman laws, and to appeal to Cæsar the Prince of the Romans not yet Christened: how much more may we call for aid of Christian Princes and their laws, for the punishment of Heretics, and for the Church's defence against them? S. Augustine ep. 50.\f*
\v 12 Then Festus having conferred with the Council, answered: Hast thou appealed to Cæsar? to Cæsar shalt thou go.
\v 13 And when certain days were passed, king Agrippa & Bernice came down to Cæsarea to salute Festus.
\v 14 And as they tarried there a good many days, Festus signified to the king, of Paul, saying: A certain person was left prisoner by Felix,
\v 15 concerning whom, when I was at Jerusalem, the chief Priests and the Ancients of the Jews came unto me, desiring condemnation against him.
\v 16 To whom I answered: That it is not the Romans' custom to yield up any man before that he which is accused have his accusers present, and take place to make his answer for to clear himself of the crimes.
\v 17 When they therefore were assembled hither, without any delay, the day following, sitting in the judgement seat, I commanded the man to be brought.
\v 18 Of whom, when the accusers stood up, they brought no cause which I thought ill of:
\v 19 but certain questions of their own superstition they had against him, and of one \sc Jesus\sc* deceased, whom Paul affirmed to live. \f + \fr 25:19 \ft This whom he termeth by contempt, one JESUS, hath now made all the Roman Emperors and Princes of the world to know him, and hath given the seat of the Cæsars to his poor servants, Peter & his successors.\f*
\v 20 Doubting therefore of this kind of question, I said, whether he would go to Jerusalem, & there be judged of these things.
\v 21 But Paul appealing to be kept unto the knowledge of Augustus, I commanded him to be kept, till I send him to Cæsar.
\v 22 And Agrippa said to Festus: Myself also would hear the man. Tomorrow, said he, thou shalt hear him.
\v 23 And the next day when Agrippa and Bernice were come with great pomp, and had entered into the hall of audience with the Tribunes and principal men of the city, at Festus' commandment Paul was brought.
\v 24 And Festus saith: King Agrippa, and all ye men that are present together with us, you see this man, concerning whom all the multitude of the Jews called upon me at Jerusalem, requesting and crying out that he ought not to live any longer.
\v 25 Yet have I found nothing that he hath committed worthy of death. But forasmuch as he himself appealed to Augustus, I have determined to send him.
\v 26 Of whom what to write for certainty to my lord, I have not. For the which cause I have brought him forth to you, and especially to thee, king Agrippa, that examination being made, I may have what to write.
\v 27 For it seemeth to me without reason, to send a prisoner, & not to signify his causes. \f + \fr 25:27 \ft c τὰς κατ ἀυτοῦ αἰτίας.\f*
\c 26
\p
\v 1 \sc But\sc* Agrippa said to Paul: Thou art permitted to speak for thyself. Then Paul stretching forth his hand, began to make his answer:
\v 2 Touching all things whereof I am accused of the Jews, king Agrippa, I account myself happy for that I am to defend myself this day before thee,
\v 3 especially whereas thou knowest all things that are among the Jews, customs and questions: for the which cause I beseech thee, hear me patiently.
\v 4 And my life truly from my youth, which was from the beginning in my nation in Jerusalem, all the Jews do know:
\v 5 knowing me before from the beginning (if they will give testimony) that according to the most sure sect of our religion I lived a Pharisee. \f + \fr 26:5 \ft c ἁίρεσιν\f*
\v 6 And now for the hope of the promise that was made of God to our fathers, do I stand subject to judgement:
\v 7 the which, our twelve tribes serving night and day, hope to come unto. Of the which hope, o king, I am accused of the Jews. \f + \fr 26:7 \ft b in quam\f* \f + \fr 26:7 \ft c λατρεῦον\f*
\v 8 What incredible thing is it judged with you, if God raise the dead?
\v 9 And myself truly had thought that I ought to do against the name of \sc Jesus\sc* of Nazareth many contrary things.
\v 10 Which also I did at Jerusalem, and many of the saints did I shut up in prisons, having received authority of the chief priests: and when they were put to death, I brought the sentence. \f + \fr 26:10 \ft c detuli sententiam.\f* \x + \xo 26:10 \xt Act. 8, 3.\x*
\v 11 And throughout all the synagogues oftentimes punishing them, I compelled them to blaspheme: and yet more mad against them, I persecuted them even unto foreign cities.
\v 12 Among which things whiles I went to Damascus with authority and permission of the chief priests, \x + \xo 26:12 \xt Act. 9, 3.\x*
\v 13 at mid-day, in the way, I saw (o king) from Heaven a light to have shined round about me and them that were in company with me, above the brightness of the sun.
\v 14 And when all we were fallen down on the ground, I heard a voice speaking to me in the Hebrew tongue: Saul, Saul, why persecutest thou me? It is hard for thee to kick against the prick.
\v 15 And I said: Who are thou Lord? And our Lord answered: I am \sc Jesus\sc* whom thou doest persecute.
\v 16 But rise up and stand upon thy feet: for to this end have I appeared to thee, that I may ordain thee a minister and witness of those things which thou hast seen, and of those things wherein I will appear to thee,
\v 17 delivering thee out of the peoples and nations unto the which now I send thee,
\v 18 to open their eyes, that they may be converted from darkness to light, and from the power of Satan to God, that they may receive remission of sins, and lot among the saints by the faith that is in me.
\v 19 Whereupon, king Agrippa, I was not incredulous to the heavenly vision:
\v 20 but to them first that are at Damascus, and at Jerusalem, and unto all the country of Jewry, and to the Gentiles did I preach that they should do penance, & turn to God, doing works worthy of penance. \f + \fr 26:20 \ft Penance often inculcated, and works agreeable to the same.\f* \x + \xo 26:20 \xt Act. 9, 20.\x*
\v 21 For this cause the Jews, when I was in the temple, apprehending me, attempted meaning to kill me. \x + \xo 26:21 \xt Act. 21, 30.\x*
\v 22 But aided by the help of God, I stand until this day, testifying to small & to great, saying nothing beside those things which the Prophets did speak should come to pass, & Moyses;
\v 23 if \sc Christ\sc* were passible, if the first of the resurrection from the dead, he were to shew light to the people and to the Gentiles.
\v 24 As he spake these things and made his answer, Festus with a loud voice said: Thou art mad, Paul; much learning turneth thee to madness.
\v 25 And Paul said: I am not mad, most excellent Festus; but I speak words of verity & sobriety.
\v 26 For the king knoweth of these things, to whom also I speak constantly. For I think none of these things to be unknown to him. For neither was any of these things done in a corner.
\v 27 Believest thou the Prophets, king Agrippa? I know that thou believest.
\v 28 And Agrippa said to Paul: A little thou persuadest me to become a \sc Christian\sc*.
\v 29 And Paul said: I wish of God, both in little, and in much, not only thee, but also all that hear this day, to become such as I am also, except these bands.
\v 30 And the king rose up, and the President, and Bernice, and they that sat by them.
\v 31 And going aside, they spake among themselves, saying, That this man hath done nothing worthy of death or bands.
\v 32 And Agrippa said to Festus: This man might be released, if he had not appealed to Cæsar.
\c 27
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* after it was decreed that he should sail into Italy, and that Paul with other prisoners should be delivered to a Centurion named Julius, of the band Augusta,
\v 2 we going up into a ship of Adrumetum, beginning to sail about the places of Asia, loosed from the land, Aristarchus the Macedonian of Thessalonica continuing with us.
\v 3 And the third day following we came to Sidon. And Julius entreating Paul courteously, permitted him to go to his friends, and to take care of himself.
\v 4 And when we had loosed thence we sailed under Cypres: because the winds were contrary.
\v 5 And sailing the sea of Cilicia and Pamphilia, we came to <alt>Lystra</alt>, which is in Lycia: \f + \fr 27:5 \ft Myra\f*
\v 6 and there the Centurion finding a ship of Alexandria sailing into Italy, removed us into it.
\v 7 And whereas many days we sailed slowly, and were scarce come over against Gnidus, the wind hindering us, we sailed near Crete by Salmone:
\v 8 and with much ado sailing by it, we came into a certain place that is called Good-havens, nigh to the which was a city Thalassa.
\v 9 And when much time was spent, and whereas now it was not safe sailing, because the fast now was past, Paul comforted them, \f + \fr 27:9 \ft It may signify the Jews' fast of the seventh month September, after which the navigation was perilous, winter approaching.\f*
\v 10 saying to them: Ye men, I see that the sailing beginneth to be with hurt and much damage, not only of the lading and the ship, but also of our lives.
\v 11 But the Centurion believed the governor and master of the ship, more than those things which were said of Paul.
\v 12 And whereas it was not a commodious haven to winter in, very many taking counsel appointed to sail thence, if by any means they might coming to Phoenice, winter there, a haven of Crete looking toward the Afrike and the Chore. \f + \fr 27:12 \ft c names of winds.\f*
\v 13 And the south-wind blowing, they thinking that they had obtained their purpose, when they had parted from Asson, sailed along by Crete.
\v 14 But not long after, a tempestuous wind that is called Euro-aquilo, drove against it.
\v 15 And when the ship was caught and could not make way against the wind, giving up the ship to the winds, we were driven,
\v 16 And running upon a certain Island, that is called Cauda, we could scarce get the cock-boat. \f + \fr 27:16 \ft c Græc. Clauda.\f*
\v 17 Which being taken up, they used helps, girding the ship, and fearing lest they should fall into the Syrt, letting down the vessel, so were they carried. \f + \fr 27:17 \ft c a place of quick sands.\f*
\v 18 And when we were mightily tossed with the tempest, the next day they cast forth.
\v 19 And the third day with their own hands they threw forth the tacklings of the ship.
\v 20 And neither sun, nor stars appearing for many days, and no small storm being toward, all hope was now taken away of our saving.
\v 21 And when there had been long fasting, then Paul standing in the midst of them, said: You should indeed, O ye men, have heard me, and not have parted from Crete, & have gained this hurt and loss.
\v 22 And now I exhort you to be of good cheer. For there shall be no loss of any soul among you, but of the ship.
\v 23 For an Angel of the God whose I am, and whom I serve, stood by me this night, \f + \fr 27:23 \ft c ᾧ λατρεύω.\f*
\v 24 saying: Fear not Paul, thou must appear before Cæsar: and behold God hath given thee all that sail with thee. \f + \fr 27:24 \ft Paul (saith S. Hierom) had so many souls in the ship given him, that is, so many men saved for his sake: and after he is with Christ, shall he shut his mouth, and not be able once to speak for them that have believed in his Gospel? Hiero. adv. Vigil. Whereby he proveth that if God do much for the merits of saints in this life, much more at their intercession & prayer in Heaven.\f*
\v 25 For the which cause be of good cheer ye men: for I believe God, that it shall so be, as it hath been said to me.
\v 26 And we must come unto a certain island.
\v 27 But after the fourteenth night was come on us, as we were sailing in Adria about mid-night, the ship-men deemed that there appeared some country to them.
\v 28 Who also sounding, found twenty fathoms: and being parted a little from thence, they found fifteen fathoms.
\v 29 And fearing lest we should fall into rough places, casting out of the stern four anchors, they wished that day were come.
\v 30 But as the ship-men sought to fly out of the ship, having let down the cock-boat into the sea, pretending as if they were about to cast out anchors out of the fore-part of the ship,
\v 31 Paul said to the Centurion and to the soldiers: unless these tarry in the ship you cannot be saved.
\v 32 Then the soldiers cut off the ropes of the cock-boat; and suffered it to fall away.
\v 33 And when it began to be light, Paul desired all to take meat, saying: This day is the fourteenth day that you expect and remain fasting, taking nothing.
\v 34 For the which cause I desire you to take meat for your health sake: for there shall not an hair of the head perish of any of you.
\v 35 And when he had said these things, taking bread he gave thanks to God in the sight of them all: and when he had broken it, he began to eat.
\v 36 And being all made of better cheer, they also took meat.
\v 37 And we were in all in the ship, souls two hundred seventy six.
\v 38 And being filled with meat, they lighted the ship, casting the wheat into the sea.
\v 39 And when day was come, they knew not the land: but they spied a certain creek that had a shore, into the which they minded, if they could, to cast aland the ship.
\v 40 And when they had taken up the anchors, they committed themselves to the sea, loosing withal the rudder bands: and hoisting up the main sail according as the wind blew, they went on toward the shore.
\v 41 And when we were fallen into a place between two seas, they graveled the ship: and the fore-part truly sticking fast remained unmoveable: but the hinder-part was broken by the violence of the sea.
\v 42 And the counsel of the soldiers was, that they should kill the prisoners: lest any swimming out, might run away.
\v 43 But the Centurion willing to save Paul, forbade it to be done: & he commanded them that could swim, to cast out themselves first, and escape, and go forth to land:
\v 44 and the rest, some they carried on boards, & some upon those things that were of the ship. And so it came to pass, that all the souls escaped to land.
\c 28
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* when we had escaped, then we knew that the island was called <alt>Mitilene</alt>. But the Barbarous shewed us no small courtesy. \f + \fr 28:1 \ft This island (now Malta) is the seat of the knights of the Rhodes: the inhabitants whereof have a special devotion to S. Paul: to whom both the chief Church (being the Bishop's Seat) is dedicated, and the whole Island (as they count it) consecrated. Where the people shew yet to strangers, his prison and other memories of his miracles.\f* \f + \fr 28:1 \ft Melita\f*
\v 2 For, kindling a fire they refreshed us all, because of the imminent rain and the cold.
\v 3 And when Paul had gathered together some number of sticks, and had laid them on the fire, a viper issuing out of the heat, invaded his hand.
\v 4 But as the Barbarous saw the beast hanging on his hand, they said one to another: Undoubtedly this man is a murderer, who being escaped out of the sea, vengeance doth not suffer him to live. \f + \fr 28:4 \ft c ἡ δίκη\f*
\v 5 and he indeed shaking off the beast into the fire, suffered no harm.
\v 6 But they supposed that he should be turned into a swelling, and that he would suddenly fall and die. But expecting long and seeing that there was no harm done on him, being changed they said, that he was a God.
\v 7 And in those places were lands of the prince of the isle, named Publius, who receiving us, for three days entreated us courteously.
\v 8 And it chanced that the father of Publius lay vexed with fevers and the bloody flux. Unto whom Paul entered: and when he had prayed, and imposed hands on him, he healed him. \f + \fr 28:8 \ft Miraculous healing by imposition of the Apostle's hands.\f*
\v 9 Which being done, all in the isle also that had infirmities, came, and were cured:
\v 10 who also honoured us with many honours, and when we were sailing away, laded us with necessaries.
\v 11 And after three months, we sailed in a ship of Alexandria, that had wintered in the island, whose sign was the Castors.
\v 12 And when we were come to Syracusa, we tarried there three days.
\v 13 Thence compassing by the shore, we came to Rhegium: and after one day the South-wind blowing, we came the second day to Puteoli,
\v 14 where finding brethren, we were desired to tarry with them seven days: and so we came to Rome.
\v 15 And from thence, when the Brethren had heard, they came to meet us unto \add Apij-forum,\add* and the Three-taverns, whom when Paul had seen, giving thanks to God, he took courage.
\v 16 And when we were come to Rome, Paul was permitted to remain to himself with a soldier that kept him.
\v 17 And after the third day he called together the chief of the Jews. And when they were assembled, he said to them: Men brethren, I doing nothing against the people, or the custom of the fathers, was delivered prisoner from Jerusalem into the hands of the Romans,
\v 18 who when they had examined me, would have released me, for that there was no cause of death in me.
\v 19 But the Jews contradicting it, I was compelled to appeal unto Cæsar, not as having any thing to accuse my nation.
\v 20 For this cause therefore I desired to see you and to speak to you. For, because of the hope of Israel, am I compassed with this chain.
\v 21 But they said to him: We neither received letters concerning thee from Jewry, neither did any of the brethren that came hither, report or speak any evil of thee.
\v 22 But we desire of thee to hear what thou thinkest: for concerning this sect, it is known to us that it is gainsaid every-where. \f + \fr 28:22 \ft c αἱρέσεως.\f*
\v 23 And when they had appointed him a day, they came to him unto his lodging very many: to whom he expounded, testifying the Kingdom of God, and using persuasion to them of \sc Jesus\sc*, out of the Law of Moyses and the Prophets, from morning until evening.
\v 24 And certain believed those things that were said: but certain believed not.
\v 25 And whereas they did not agree among themselves, they departed, Paul saying one word: That well did the Holy Ghost speak by Esaie the Prophet to our fathers,
\v 26 saying: \add Go to this people, and say to them: With the ear you shall hear, and shall not understand: and seeing you shall see and shall not perceive.\add* \x + \xo 28:26 \xt Esa. 6, 9. Mat. 13, 14. Mr. 4, 12. Lu. 8, 10. Io. 12, 40. Ro. 11, 8.\x*
\v 27 \add For the heart of this people is waxen gross, and with their ears have they heavily heard, and their eyes \add* \add they have shut: lest perhaps they may see with their eyes, and hear with their ears, and understand with their heart, and be converted, and I heal them.\add* \f + \fr 28:27 \ft Here also (as Mat. 13.) it is plain that they would not see, nor hear, & that their excecation is to be attributed to themselves & not to God. See annota. Io. 12, 40.\f*
\v 28 Be it known therefore to you, that this Salvation of God is sent to the Gentiles, and they will hear.
\v 29 And when he had said these things, the Jews went out from him, having much questioning among themselves.
\v 30 And he tarried full two years in his hired lodging: and he received all that came in to him,
\v 31 preaching the Kingdom of God, and teaching the things that concern our Lord \sc Jesus Christ\sc* with all confidence, without prohibition.
